<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow holds up despite receding
rate cut hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
SHARE PRICES were little changed yesterday after investors shrugged off
comments from Mr Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve, which
appeared to rule out another interest rate cut, writes Patrick Harverson in
New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished just 6.49 up at 3,251.57, the
index having rarely strayed from its overnight close all day. The more
broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was a slight 0.01 easier at 413.76,
while the Nasdaq composite of over-the-counter stocks failed to hold on to
an early gain, ending 0.76 off at 633.37.
New York SE turnover came to a moderate 200m shares and rises narrowly
outpaced declines by 949 to 753, an indication of the market's underlying
firm tone.
Although investors remain sensitive to changes in monetary policy - recent
gains have been fuelled by hopes of another interest rate reduction - they
chose to ignore statements by Mr Greenspan yesterday which indicated he was
satisfied that the last interest rate move, a one percentage point cut in
the discount rate on December 20, would be sufficient to spur the US economy
towards a solid recovery.
Attention focused on individual corporate stories, in particular on
quarterly results. Goodyear Tire climbed Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 61 3/8
after announcing fourth-quarter income of Dollars 105.1m, a big improvement
on the Dollars 11.6m earned at the same stage of 1990.
Corning Glass declined Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 29 7/8 and Dow Chemical lost
Dollars 1 to Dollars 56 1/4 as the controversy surrounding the silicone
breast implants manufactured by Dow Corning, jointly owned by the two
companies, continued.
Following a delayed opening due to an order imbalance on the buy side,
Greyhound rose Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 10 3/8 on the American Stock
Exchange after an analyst at Legg Mason Wood Walker issued an initial buy
recommendation, arguing that the company, which emerged from bankruptcy last
October, is well positioned to benefit from its role as the only US national
bus operation.
Deere &amp; Co advanced Dollars 1 initially but ended only Dollars  1/4 up at
Dollars 51 5/8 in the wake of an upgrade from Bear Stearns, the broking
house, which now rates the agricultural equipment maker's stock a 'buy'.
First Fidelity Bancorp firmed Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 33 3/4 after Alex
Brown &amp; Sons added the stock to its 'emphasis' list for institutional
clients, citing the group's capital strength, asset quality improvement and
operating efficiencies.
On the over-the-counter market, Medical Graphics jumped Dollars 3 1/8 to
Dollars 16 1/4 in active trading after the US Food and Drug Administration
granted approval for the company's pulmonary function diagnostic system.
Canada
WEAKNESS in commodity prices led to moderate losses in Toronto stocks.
Causing the market to ease further towards the end of the day was the US
Treasury auction of three-year notes, which produced results weaker than
expected.
The composite index ended 10.6 down at 3,597.8, with declining issues
leading advances by 305 to 289. Volume totalled 29.4m shares.
Finning fell CDollars 1 to CDollars 13 1/8 after the company announced a
loss of CDollars 1.3m in the fourth quarter, against a profit of CDollars
4.0m a year earlier.
Alberta Natural Gas reported lower income from continuing operations in the
fourth quarter, but the stock gained CDollars  1/4 to CDollars 13.
</TEXT>
