<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / Foreign Exchanges: Dollar rises against D-Mark
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DOLLAR strengthened against the D-Mark yesterday, spurred by
speculators, rumours and the increasing perception that the Federal Reserve
would not cut rates, writes Peggy Hollinger.
The US unit jumped almost two pfennigs against the D-Mark in the morning,
before Mr Alan Greenspan, Fed chairman, spoke to US bankers.
Although he left his options open for a further rate reduction, Mr Greenspan
said he felt existing actions would be sufficient to prompt recovery. The
economic pay-off should come soon, he added.
Bolstering his statement, Washington-based consultancy Johnson and Smick
issued its own view that the Fed would not cut rates in the near term.
The dollar closed in London up two pfennigs at DM1.5905. The DM1.59 rate was
seen as a key support level. In New York it finished at DM1.5955.
The dollar is expected to trade within a fairly narrow range while the
market waits for the next significant economic data from the US. Retail
sales for January, to be published tomorrow, are expected to be flat.
Dollar sentiment was also boosted by talk that the Bank of Switzerland would
not prevent a sharp fall in the Swiss franc. Although the bank denied the
rumours, the damage had been done and the US currency strengthened from
SFr1.4040 to close at SFr1.4240 in London.
The yen weakened against the dollar in line with the D-Mark's fall. At one
stage, the Japanese unit hit Y127.50 against the dollar - close to the level
at which the Fed and the Bank of Japan intervened last month. But the rate
fell back to Y126.85, just 15 basis points above Monday's close. It rose in
New York to Y127.48.
A senior trader said there had been 'good interest' in dollar for yen trade
from Japanese banks.
Sterling also took some heat from a stronger dollar, falling in London from
Dollars 1.8260 to Dollars 1.8015. However, within the European exchange rate
mechanism, the pound appeared undeterred by speculation of a rate cut in the
UK.
It weakened only slightly against the D-Mark, from DM2.8675 to DM2.8650.
'The powers that be would be encouraged by sterling's performance against a
background of rumoured rate cuts,' said one dealer.
Paradoxically, when the Bank of England signalled that it would not cut
yesterday, sterling actually fell 20 to 30 points, the dealer added.
Rumours were rife during the day that the Spanish and British central banks
would simultaneously cut rates at some stage.
The peseta's lead within the ERM is keeping sterling pressed against the
limit of its allowed divergence from the central ecu rate. The pound ended
at Pta 180.68/78, virtually brushing the ERM floor of Pta 180.59.
Spanish inflation figures are to be published tomorrow, which could offer
the opportunity of a rate cut in Spain.
</TEXT>
