FT  12 FEB 92 / International Company News: Stelco and Dofasco slip into red
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CANADA'S two biggest steelmakers, Dofasco and Stelco, suffered a combined
loss of more than CDollars 160m (USDollars 136.7m) in 1991, exacerbated by a
sharp deterioration in business conditions towards the end of the year.
Dofasco's loss was CDollars 25m, or 73 cents a share, compared with a loss
after writedowns of CDollars 679.2m, or CDollars 10.64, in 1990.
The bulk of the 1990 loss came from the write-off of the company's CDollars
713m investment in Algoma Steel. Revenues dipped to CDollars 2.06bn from
CDollars 2.36bn.
Stelco suffered a net loss of CDollars 136m, or CDollars 3.05 a share,
against the 1990 loss of CDollars 197m, or CDollars 5.96 a share. Revenues
edged down to CDollars 2bn from CDollars 2.09bn.
Dofasco's fourth-quarter loss was CDollars 1.5m, including an operating loss
of CDollars 24.4m.
Stelco said that an improvement in its financial performance in the first
nine months of last year came to an 'abrupt' halt, which left it CDollars
38m in the red in the final three months.
It blamed the fourth-quarter setback on a sharp price decline caused by the
need to find new markets for higher-value products earmarked for the
automotive industry.
Dofasco said that demand for flat rolled steel dropped by 10 per cent last
year, and 24 per cent below the peak of 1988. Total steel shipments dipped
by 6 per cent in the fourth quarter to 872,000 tons.
</TEXT>
