<TEXT>
BLACK &amp; Decker, the US household equipment-maker and information services
provider, yesterday unveiled a fourth-quarter profit of Dollars 31.9m,
thanks primarily to lower interest expenses and a turnround in earnings from
its Brazilian operations. In the same quarter of 1990, the company earned
just Dollars 6.8m.
For the full-year, Black &amp; Decker made a net profit of Dollars 53m, a modest
improvement on the Dollars 51.1m earned a year earlier. Revenues for the
year fell slightly to Dollars 4.6bn, due mostly to recessions in three big
markets - the US, the UK and Australia.
The company was encouraged by stronger-than-expected domestic fourth-quarter
sales, particularly of its power tools, household products and Kwikset
locks, and by its low inventories.
Black &amp; Decker's figures were well received on Wall Street, and the shares
rose Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 24 5/8 on the New York Stock Exchange.
