<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / International Company News: Federal Express considers
restructuring
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FEDERAL Express, the Memphis-based express package delivery company,
yesterday confirmed market suspicions that it is actively looking to
restructure its international operations, although it would notspeculate on
when any decisions might be reached.
After the company's shares shot Dollars 3 1/2 higher yesterday on heavy
volume, Federal Express released a formal statement saying it had been
considering various options aimed at reducing its losses overseas.
These options, said the company, could include restructurings as well as
co-operative or other business arrangements with third parties. Preliminary
talks had been held with various outside parties, it added, but the delivery
company stressed the examination of available options was 'at this stage,
exploratory only'.
It stated 'no conclusions have been reached with respect to any courses of
action the company may take, nor have there been any agreements with third
parties'. On the stock market, final volume in Federal Express shares
totalled 1.54m, against an average daily trading of 166,400 shares.
The bulk of Federal Express's problems overseas have come in Europe and the
UK. Last spring, the company took a Dollars 121m charge against earnings to
cover workforce and other cuts in the UK and a large part of its British
operation has been sold back to Littlewoods, the privately-owned UK
retailer.
But in the second quarter of its current financial year - to end-November -
Federal Express still reported operating losses of Dollars 64.5m, up from
Dollars 54.7m a year earlier and said it was 'disgusted' with the
performance.
Analysts have speculated that, while it would be difficult for the company
to abandon service to European destinations for competitive reasons, it
could try to cut fixed costs by using third party agents or entering into
joint venture arrangements on a regional basis.
</TEXT>
