<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / UK Company News: British Aerospace pays Asda Pounds 79m -
New row breaks out over option in dispute about joint venture
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH AEROSPACE yesterday announced that it had paid Pounds 79m to resolve
a dispute with Asda, the supermarket group, over an ill-starred joint
venture.
However, a new row broke out over an option which could force BAe to buy out
its partner, potentially for some Pounds 75m.
Arlington, BAe's property subsidiary, said the option was irrelevant. It
only applied in the event of a default and so it was invalidated by the
payment of the Pounds 79m, it said.
'Any action against Arlington will be vigorously contested,' the company
added.
Mr Paul Dowling, corpor- ate affairs director for Asda Group, said that
Asda's lawyers took a different view. 'Our legal advice is that we have a
put option. It is clear.'
Mr Dowling said that Asda had not decided whether it would exercise its
option. 'We are reviewing the situation,' he said.
It is unclear what value would be placed on a half share of the Burwood
House Group, the joint venture.
However, it would probably be less than Pounds 75m, the equity injected by
both partners when it was set up.
The joint venture was set up two years ago, just before BAe took over
Arlington, partly to help Asda raise cash to finance its acquisition of 61
Gateway stores.
Gazeley Holdings, part of Asda, put 34 of its stores, then valued at Pounds
350m, into the group and extracted Pounds 275m of cash. Arlington injected a
number of shopping schemes, then valued at Pounds 75m.
Arlington guaranteed the value of these development sites when it set up the
joint venture. Its payment of Pounds 79m into Burwood House arose from its
obligation to make good a shortfall in value of the development properties.
'The decision was the most beneficial to British Aerospace after considering
various proposals designed to protect the position of the joint venture
company and the interest of both its shareholders,' it said in a statement
to the Stock Exchange.
It added that the payment avoided 'any question' arising from an option that
would require Arlington to sell its interest in the Burwood House Group to
Gazeley or to buy Gazeley's interest in the Burwood House Group, at open
market value. BAe had already made provision for the payment in its 1991
accounts.
Both companies have been under severe pressure recently. A month ago, Asda
reported a pre-tax loss of Pounds 68.8m for the half year to November 9. In
recent months BAe has seen the failure of a Pounds 432m right issues, a
heavy fall in profits and the departure of senior managers.
BAe's share price fell from 295p to 282p. Asda's share price was unchanged
at 38 1/2p.
</TEXT>
