<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / Gatt urges 'rainforest payments'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INDUSTRIAL countries should pay nations such as Brazil and Indonesia for the
'carbon absorption services' provided by their rainforests, a report
published today argues.
The report on trade and the environment from the Geneva-based General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade says that this would be more effective in
curbing deforestation than attempts to ban trade in logs.
The proposal illustrates a broader concern that trade measures - whether
tariff walls, export bans or duties - are ineffective in tackling
environmental problems. Mr Arthur Dunkel, Gatt director general, warned
yesterday against the environment issue 'being kidnapped by trade
protectionist interests'.
The report is published four months ahead of the Rio 'earth summit', and is
intended to provide a focus for what is expected to be a heated debate on
trade and the environment.
It says rainforest states are 'effectively exporting, free of charge, carbon
absorption services to the rest of the world'.
Gatt says an export ban on timber would not halt deforestation. These
exports account for less than 1 per cent of trees felled in developing
countries, whereas 80 per cent are felled as fuel for people unable to
afford other fuels.
It calls for international agreement on plans to halt deforestation which
would include compensation to countries with large rainforests, employment
promotion policies in these countries and improved access to industrial
markets for their exports.
