<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / Charter stresses staff rights: Government plans to encourage
legally enforceable contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday issued a 'United Kingdom Social Charter', stressing
rights for the individual at work and new training opportunities.
The main piece of legislation planned in the employment white paper requires
that individual employment contracts give employees more details of their
terms and conditions.
The white paper supplements plans for another round of restrictions on trade
unions in an earlier green paper.
It also aims to make the poaching of skilled workers more difficult.
The government wants to encourage legally enforceable contracts which would
allow employers to recoup some of the cost of training if an employee left
within a certain period. In both areas the government will consult before
legislating.
In the field of training, the main new ideas are to extend the credits
concept to careers advice for adults in work wishing to expand their
employment opportunities and to provide 'open learning' vouchers, in
conjunction with libraries, for the unemployed.
Mr Michael Howard, employment secretary, told the Commons, to Labour
laughter, that the training proposals would be paid for out of existing
budgets. The 'skill-check' credit scheme will cost Pounds 25m over the next
two years and will be launched in 15 Training and Enterprise Councils.
The white paper is a political argument against the employment proposals of
the Labour party and the European Community Social Charter.
However, it implicitly acknowledges the impact of Labour's accusation that
the Conservative employment agenda was merely negative 'union-bashing'.
It also borrows from Labour's new emphasis on individual rights in relation
to the employer, as opposed to the recent Conservative emphasis on
individual rights in relation to the trade union.
Many of the original green paper proposals are still there, including the
right of employees to join the union of their choice regardless of the
Trades Union Congress rulings.
The white paper stresses the superiority of individual dealings with
employers, hence the new detail that employers will probably have to provide
in employment contracts. That detail goes beyond what is required through
adoption of the EC's Directive on Proof of Employment Relationships.
Mr Howard cited as proof that collective bargaining was no longer effective
the fact that people covered by collective bargaining now earned on average
Pounds 7.50 a week less than those not so covered. Pay analysts pointed out,
however, that white-collar pay had grown three times faster than manual pay
in the 1980s.
Mr Tony Blair, Labour's employment spokesman, criticised the plan to make
employees liable for the cost of their training but said it was 'a
fundamental concession' to the Labour view that a voluntary approach on
training was insufficient.
White paper details, Page 5
Transfer fees, Page 11
