<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / Planned rise in EC revenue may reawaken old quarrels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STRASBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Commission last night agreed proposals to raise Community
budget revenue by a third over the next five years. Officials fear the
package could lead to a re-opening of budgetary squabbles between the UK and
other EC members.
Under the Commission plan, unanimously approved last night, EC revenue would
rise from Ecu66bn (Pounds 47bn) this year to Ecu88bn in 1997, at 1992
prices.
The 1993-97 financial plan, which Mr Jacques Delors, Commission president,
is due to present to the European Parliament today, aims to double fiscal
transfers to Spain, Ireland, Portugal and Greece in order to help them
prepare for economic and monetary union (Emu).
If member states approve the plan, several countries undergoing fiscal
strain will be asked to contribute significantly more than they do now, and
there are clear signs that some will fight hard to shift part of the burden.
Germany, the EC's main paymaster, is straining to finance unification and
pay for its large east European aid programme. It has already asked the
Commission to re-examine the budget rebate the UK has received since 1985.
A senior Commission official said yesterday, however, that this would not
happen until after the UK general election.
The Financial Times has obtained normally confidential details on the net
contributions made by EC governments. These illustrate why some countries
are likely to demand revisions to the budget.
Germany this year is contributing a net Ecu9bn to the EC's budget. The UK -
the second largest net contributor - would contribute just over Ecu5bn but
would receive more than Ecu2bn 'abatement'. This was originally won by Mrs
Margaret Thatcher, the former UK prime minister, because Britain gets
proportionally less than its comparable partners from the farm budget, which
still accounts for 54 per cent of EC spending.
Although contributions from both countries, and from France, the other main
net contributor, are set to rise, Germany wants a redistribution of
financial responsibility. 'It is pretty obvious that we have to talk about
the UK rebate again,' a German official said.
Belgium and Italy, two countries intent on entering Emu in the first wave
later this decade, will be particularly hard hit. Belgium, like Denmark and
the Netherlands, usually fares better under the EC budget than its high per
capita income would justify. Italy's position fluctuates; this year it will
take Ecu600m net out of the budget but in 1991 it contributed a net Ecu400m.
However, both Belgium and Italy face uphill struggles to cut public
indebtedness and budget deficits to meet the stiff Emu conditions by 1999.
The Commission, concerned to contain the budgetary squabbles it fears will
break out, insisted yesterday that the overall benefit of EC membership
cannot be quantified simply in budgetary contributions.
