<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / Collapse of the second Guiness Trial: 'I haven't been beaten
by much in my life' - The case that brought a city financier close to
breakdown
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT IS the sense of incompleteness, with its implication almost of personal
failure, that seems most to concern Mr Roger Seelig about the ending of his
six-year ordeal arising from the notorious Guinness affair.
On the eve of the end of his trial, he said: 'I think we have conducted this
defence very well and it is a great disappointment to me not to be able to
finish it . . . I never failed to complete a bid and I'm very disappointed
to have failed to complete this.
'What I have really had to recognise is that the physical task was just too
great. It is very, very hard to convey that to someone who has not had to do
it. I haven't been beaten by much in my life and it is a great
disappointment to find that you just can't do it.
'I really wanted an acquittal and I'm deeply disappointed at not achieving
that through lack of physical stamina.'
For more than four months, Mr Seelig conducted his own defence to fraud and
false accounting charges. Faced with legal bills running into several
hundred thousand pounds and 'the recognition that the costs are completely
uncontrollable', he decided lawyers were a luxury he could no longer afford.
'The expenses are quite, quite beyond anything that any salaried employee,
however successful, can possibly sustain in trials that go on for a year or
more. To have been represented by a full legal team over the past
two-and-a-half or more years would have cost perhaps Pounds 3m.
'My highest salary at Morgans was only Pounds 110,000 before tax, though
admittedly there were bonuses. The legal aid regulations are not devised for
working professionals. They look at your gross assets without taking into
account your gross debts.'
Had he had any idea of what he was letting himself in for by conducting his
own defence?
'No. I knew it would be a considerable effort but I think I thought that one
would be capable of seeing that through to the end. When I was at Morgans we
really did work all the waking hours, so I thought I could cope with this.
But it is different.'
His typical working day would begin at 8am when he would arrive at the house
of his friend Mr George Devlin. Together they would prepare for the day's
hearing until it was time to leave for Southwark Crown Court. When the court
day ended they would work together into the night.
For much of the trial Mr Devlin, a sometime legal clerk, private
investigator and property businessman, also sat in court as Mr Seelig's
'McKenzie friend' - a term arising from a case in which it was held that an
unrepresented defendant could have the assistance of someone to take notes
and generally help in the conduct of his case.
Mr Seelig seemed surprised to be told there had been general admiration in
court for the way in which he handled his defence, at least in the early
stages. Had he really been as confident as he had seemed?
'No, I felt enormously nervous and apprehensive but strengthened, if you
like, by the amount of preparation we had done and the feeling of being
well-briefed.'
It had been a month to six weeks into the trial when he started to feel the
strain. Apart from the workload there had been the mental tension.
'I have not been depressed - and this is an important statement, I think - I
have not been depressed at all with the way the trial was going, in fact the
opposite: I believe we have been well ahead on points. That has not been
part of the stress factor. What you find is it just physically gets you
down.
'I was literally only putting papers down when I went to sleep. And then if
I woke up in the middle of the night I would go and get them. When I woke up
next morning I would get them before getting out of bed, because there isn't
enough time to do it.
'Another thing is you don't get positive feedback. I used to work just as
hard, in terms of hours, at Morgans, but you'd get successes along the way
in the sense of you'd have a successful bid and there would be a sense of a
completed job well done. This job not only wasn't complete, it seemed just
to stretch endlessly.
'We started off expecting a three-month trial, then it became a four-month
trial, then six months, and the last estimates were going through to March
1993, and even those were predicated on a very limited defence.
'There's a limit psychologically - it's very disturbing being in an endless
tunnel.'
Around the time the trial broke for Christmas he was becoming mentally and
physically exhausted. He went to his GP and a consultant psychiatrist with
the request that 'they find a way of strengthening me to complete the task.
The defence, in my view, was going so well I believed that if I could
complete it I would get the acquittal that I wanted.'
Apart from the strain, had there been any specific cause for his emotional
outbursts that had punctuated the trial?
One factor, he believed, was a deep sense of frustration when
cross-examining former colleagues. 'Perhaps if I had been a QC I would have
found it easier to have attacked those people openly and roughly.
'The whole of my working life I gave to Morgans and made a significant
contribution to the house. And it's a matter of deep feeling that not only
were they not prepared to stand by me but they actually tried to make me a
scapegoat.'
When had he realised that he would be in serious trouble if the trial went
on? He supposed it had been brought home to him on January 29 when he had
had 'a sort of collapse' in court. I'm not a particularly emotional person.
I don't think I have really cried about anything in my life and when you
find that you are unable to control yourself then clearly the body is
telling you something - that you've reached a point of physical and mental
exhaustion. I suddenly realised it was getting worse rather than better.
There was no respite from the work and it was going from bad to worse in
terms of concentration and performance. It's as if you have got a mental
block.'
Had he expected to be arrested?
'No, I don't think I did because I think it goes back to the question of did
I think I had done anything dishonest. I knew there was no question of a
ha'penny of personal gain or benefit. And as I said on the day I left
Morgans, I had only ever tried to do what I believed to be in the best
interests of the client and the house throughout my whole career.
'This was the largest, roughest contested bid there had ever been but one
had tried to operate within the framework as one understood it.' If, he
added, he had been guilty of anything, it had been overzealousness rather
than dishonesty.
How did he see his future?
'The immediate future has to be a rest, but I have absolutely no doubt that
having had a rest there will be no permanent damage in any way - indeed the
doctors have indicated that. I've equally no doubt that the financial world
is absolutely in my blood and in one way or another, whether as principal or
consultant or whatever, I shall have to find a way of participating in it
and earning a living.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
