<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / Signs of housing revival reported
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HOUSING market may be showing faint signs of recovering from the deepest
depression in its history, the National Association of Estate Agents said
yesterday.
A survey of 150 members of the association suggests viewings and offers by
potential buyers are increasing.
Two thirds of estate agents said offers from prospective buyers in January
were up on monthly levels in the final quarter of last year and 84 per cent
said viewings had increased.
Estate agents in London, the region hardest hit by the property market
depression, say inquiries are up for the first time in many months.
Agents believe house prices will be flat for at least another year, however,
until the middle of next year.
Mr David Ware, president of the National Association of Estate Agencies,
said: 'I am very pleased with the increased activity but I am acutely aware
that we experienced a similar blip this time last year, when the revival
proved to be a false dawn.'
Regions where the signs of a housing market revival are strongest include
the north and north-west of England, the west Midlands, London and East
Anglia.
In another survey published yesterday, private house builders report an
increase in sales in January compared with a year ago.
Firms in the south-east told the House Builders' Federation there had been
the first 'strong upturn' in the market since August 1988.
The federation said the findings suggested a housing market recovery was
under way, 'as the first signs of market improvement normally ripple
outwards from London and the south-east'.
In the survey of builders, 62 per cent said sales had increased last month
compared with January last year. Only 21 per cent said sales fell.
In Greater London, 62 per cent said sales had improved while 33 per cent
said they had remained the same.
</TEXT>
