<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / Mortgage market monitor urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A HOUSEBUYERS' council to regulate the mortgage lending industry and improve
consumer protection and information was yesterday urged by the Catholic
Housing Aid Society.
The charity recommended the move after a study it conducted on repossessions
found that restrictive lender practices, reinforced by a lack of consumer
information, contributed to the rising tide of repossessions. Judges in
county courts were criticised for being unwilling to exercise their
discretion to postpone repossessions.
The housebuyers' council would be responsible for creating a more
competitive and efficient mortgage market by developing 'an appropriate
regulatory and consumer information framework'. Members of the council would
include representatives of government departments, regulators such as the
Office of Fair Trading, the Council of Mortgage Lenders and consumer
representatives.
Its tasks would include:
Registering and regulating lenders - mortgages offered by unregistered
bodies would not be legally enforceable.
Setting a maximum mortgage of 95 per cent of valuation.
Establishing a regional network of independent advice centres for
housebuyers.
Developing and enforcing a code of practice for lenders dealing with
arrears.
The study is based on 60 repossession cases taken from the files of National
Debtline, a Birmingham-based telephone hotline.
Mr Mark Boleat, director-general of the CML, said he would support a more
coherent regulatory framework. He warned, however, that it would not be easy
to create such a framework given the existing legislation on consumer
credit, finan-cial services and estate agencies.
Repossessed. CHAS, 189A Old Brompton Road, London SW5 0AR. Pounds 7.50.
</TEXT>
