FT  12 FEB 92 / Index plan to assess council reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A 'COMMUNITY INDEX' to evaluate the intangible costs and benefits of
reorganising local government is suggested by advisers preparing the
government guidance to be given to the planned local government commission.
The commission, charged with the largest review of local government since
the present structure was established in 1973, will be set up after the
local government bill is enacted in the next few weeks.
The report by CSL Group, published yesterday for consultation with local
authority associations and the Audit Commission, the local government
watchdog, looks both at financial costs and benefits and those which are
less straightforward. Among intangible effects, ministers have emphasised
the need for authorities to have a strong local identity. The report
emphasises accessibility, democracy and responsiveness.
The four elements cover factors such as physical geography, historical
identities, co-ordination of services, high election turnouts and the
adverse effect of losing experienced councillors and officers. Each proposal
for re-structuring would be judged on how it measured up against the index.
While the index is intended to minimise subjectivity in assessing the
intangible effects of changes, the report accepts that where financial and
non-financial effects point in different directions, decisions will be up to
the commission.
</TEXT>
