<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / Action by Lloyd's Names: Victory that will spark more action
 -Pounds 116m Outhwaite settlement is significant triumph for those who
acted to recover heavy losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YESTERDAY'S Pounds 116m out-of-court settlement in the Outhwaite case is a
clear victory for the Lloyd's Names who backed the suit.
It is bound to encourage further legal action by other Names - the
individuals whose capital backs the market - who face some of their worst
losses in the 300-year history of the insurance market.
One Outhwaite Name said: 'The message for other action groups is that if
you've got a good legal team you've a chance of getting your money back.'
The settlement ends the biggest legal action at Lloyd's, which has been
dogged by controversy over the last 10 years. With losses from US court
awards to the victims of asbestosis and a wave of natural catastrophes
mounting, relations between Names and their agents, who handle the affairs
of Names and manage syndicates, have been troubled.
In the Outhwaite case, Names took action to recover more than Pounds 125m in
insurance losses stemming from 32 reinsurance contracts assumed in 1982 by
the underwriter of Lloyd's syndicate 317/661, Mr Richard Outhwaite. Overall
losses for the 1,614 Names on the syndicate amount to more than Pounds 200m
and are rising.
The contracts reinsured the exposures of other insurers, mainly other
Lloyd's syndicates, to US liability risks and particularly asbestosis
awards. The Names alleged negligence and breach of contract by the RHM
Outhwaite Underwriting agency, which managed syndicate 317/661, and by 80
other agents who funnelled them on to Mr Outhwaite's syndicate.
The Outhwaite action is one of six legal cases in which Names have alleged
their losses arose because of negligence of agents in four cases, and the
Corporation of Lloyd's in the other.
Four of these cases involving Pulbrook syndicates 90 and 334, Poland 105 and
108 and four Oakeley Vaughan syndicates, are unsettled. Names who have not
yet joined those actions are bound to note that Outhwaite Names who followed
advice against joining the Outhwaite suit now find themselves left out in
the cold by the settlement.
Moreover, the success of the Outhwaite Names' settlement contrasts sharply
with that achieved last week by more than 500 members of Warrilow syndicate
553 who sued their agents for losses of more than Pounds 60m. Their campaign
ran out of steam, forcing the Names to accept a settlement which met about
10 per cent of losses.
Mr Peter Nutting, a Name in the Outhwaite syndicate and the leader of the
campaign to recover losses, said yesterday: 'The size of this settlement may
have the effect of encouraging some people who were hesitant about joining
action groups to to join them.'
His assertion is supported by the experience this week of Mr David Tiplady
of solicitors DJ Freeman, who is acting for about 1,000 Names in three
actions involving Pulbrook and Poland Names.
At the end of last week 280 of the 570 Names on Pulbrook 334 in 1985 were
party to an action against Lloyd's agents. In addition, 330 of the 478
members of Pulbrook 90 and only about 350 of more than 900 Names who were
members of Poland syndicates were backing actions.
Mr Tiplady says he has been 'flooded' with calls in the wake of the
Outhwaite settlement. One managing agent at Lloyd's said yesterday writs
were going to fly 'like confetti'.
The main concern for authorities at Lloyd's must be the position of several
thousand Names on syndicates managed by Feltrim, Gooda Walker, Devonshire
and Rose Thomson Young. These specialised in catastrophe reinsurance and
face losses of more than Pounds 500m as claims roll in from natural
disasters between 1987 and 1990.
Although no liability was apportioned in the Outhwaite settlement, expert
evidence on Mr Outhwaite's behalf by Mr Richard Hazell, a fellow Lloyd's
underwriter and deputy chairman of Lloyd's, may have influenced the defence
to opt for a settlement. Mr Hazell defended Mr Outhwaite from charges of
negligence but accepted that the underwriter had been 'imprudent in some
respects'.
He accepted that Mr Outhwaite had not foreseen the scale of potential losses
when he underwrote 32 run-off reinsurance contracts. Mr Hazell admitted that
many of the alleged shortcomings of Mr Outhwaite's underwriting - such as
poor record-keeping - were typical of the market at the time. 'If Mr
Outhwaite was living in a cocoon we all were,' Mr Hazell said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-9370</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CBLA2AECFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920212
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / GEC Alsthom dispute fuelled by job cut threat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN INDUSTRIAL dispute at a plant of GEC Alsthom, the switchgear company, has
intensified after management told unions it wants to shed a further 157
jobs.
About 430 of the 650-strong workforce at Openshaw, near Manchester, have
been on strike for more than five weeks over the compulsory redundancy of 12
people.
These were part of a shedding of 95 jobs announced in September.
Negotiations on a settlement to the dispute will inevitably be complicated
by the further job losses.
GEC Alsthom had previously indicated that more job losses were necessary,
but unions say that 157 is worse than they had feared. The company may seek
volunteers for the cuts. Unions, however, believe it will seek further
compulsory severances.
Many groups of workers have threatened industrial action over redundancies
in the recession but few have taken it. Strikes on any issue have been rare
in the past year.
The GEC Alsthom strikers will be told by unions today of the management
plans, which also include a reduction in the size of the plant.
The company said yesterday that the workforce reduction was because of
depressed demand for medium-voltage switchgear equipment and the need to cut
costs to compete. Orders had declined further since the 95 redundancies were
announced.
The company said it regretted the compulsory redundancies. Continued efforts
were being made to resolve the dispute before the company suffered
irreparable dam-age.
Mr Larry Brooke, national officer of the MSF general technical union, said
the strikers were not fighting for money but the right to work. Workers from
the plant yesterday demonstrated about redundancies outside GEC's London
headquarters.
GEC Alsthom is owned 50 per cent by GEC and 50 per cent by Alcatel of
France.
</TEXT>
