<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / Conservatives follow Labour lead in focusing on the
individual: Employment White Paper - People, Jobs and Opportunity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH and DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR claims to have been first off the mark. To stress its distance from
the old collectivism it has been promising a charter to increase the rights
of individuals at work.
Yesterday - in a white paper entitled People, Jobs and Opportunity - the
Conservative party outlined its plans for 'unlocking the potential of each
and every individual' by widening choice and freedom and, in some cases,
increasing rights. 'There is a new recognition of the role and importance of
the individual employee,' it said.
In the past 13 years individual rights at work have meant, for the
Conservatives, the right to challenge the trade union collective. Labour's
accusation that proposals in the original green paper on employment were
just the 'old agenda' of negative union-bashing appears to have struck home.
For the Conservatives to adopt the theme of individual rights at work will
seem like a bad joke to many trade unionists. They say the labour market
de-regulation of the past decade has stripped workers of rights by, for
example, denying people the right to appeal against unfair dismissal until
they have been employed for two years.
The Conservatives, however, do not have Labour's problem of trying to marry
individual rights with collective ones. Emphasising the continuing
differences with Labour, the white paper rejects the 'increasingly
inappropriate patterns of industrial relations, based on collective
bargaining and collective agreements'.
Labour's backing for ideas such as a national minimum wage and works
councils - and the European Community's attempts to introduce uniform models
of industrial relations - are rejected in favour of a less prescriptive
approach. 'Much depends on the actions of employers . . . the government's
role is to create the framework within which individual choice and
opportunity can flourish.'
The white paper, which in places has the tentative air of a green paper, is
very much a political document. But it includes suggestions for best
practice which employers should follow as well as changes to the law. The
proposals include:
Terms of employment: Laws would be introduced to give every employee working
more than eight hours a week the right to a statement on his or her terms
and conditions of employment within two months of starting work. Employees
going to work abroad would be entitled to receive additional information
before departure.
The statement would include information about pay, hours of work and
holidays and, possibly, training. Any changes would be notified by the
employer directly to individuals in writing. The government proposes to
extend the jurisdiction of industrial tribunals so they are able to decide
complaints about breaches of employment contracts when an employee leaves.
Poaching of trained employees: The government floats the idea of legislation
that would make it harder for employers to poach workers trained by other
organisations. Employers 'may want to offer training under a contract which
provides for the individual to work for a period after training or repay
some of the costs'. The government is considering simplifying the procedure
for training contracts by bringing them within the jurisdiction of
industrial tribunals.
Voucher scheme for careers advice: These will be on offer in some areas from
April 1993 and are aimed at strengthening career information, assessment and
counselling services for adults who are, in the main, already in employment.
The white paper does not detail who will be entitled to the vouchers but the
idea would be to concentrate on the lowest skilled and lowest paid. Young
people are entitled by law to help from their local careers service. The
white paper says provision for adults is 'variable'.
A few of the employer-led training and enterprise councils (Tecs) are
piloting a careers-advice voucher scheme offering credits of between about
Pounds 60 and Pounds 120 to individuals. A total of 15 Tecs will be involved
in extending the scheme and it is intended 250,000 people will benefit over
two years.
Individual training accounts: An individual and the employer would
contribute jointly over time to an 'account' for training. The white paper
makes no specific proposals but says the government 'believes that this is
an approach worth testing further'. Tecs will be asked to organise pilot
projects.
Home study: Vocational 'open learning' materials and back-up services will
be available in local libraries over the next three years. Pilot schemes
will be set up by Tecs to make vouchers available to unemployed people so
they can buy home-study books, courses and support.
Flexible working: The Department of Employment will soon publish a guide on
the benefits of flexible working, providing good-practice guidance on
annualised hours, career breaks and working from home. It will continue to
oppose European Commission proposals to restrict working hours
'unnecessarily'.
Equal opportunities: A government minister will chair a proposed advisory
group to assist in encouraging and disseminating good employment practice
for older workers. The white paper says employers sometimes forget the value
of older workers but says legislation on age limits in recruitment and other
issues would be ineffective. The Employment Department plans guidance on
sexual harassment.
Trade unions: As first outlined in a green paper last autumn individuals
would be given greater freedom to join the union of their choice, a right to
more financial information about it and a right to restrain unlawful
organisation of industrial action in a public service they use. Union
members would be 'protected' against abuses of 'check-off' arrangements
under which subscriptions are deducted from salary.
Poaching employees, Page 11
Letters, Page 17
</TEXT>
