<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / Oil workers' group wins recognition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OFFSHORE Industry Liaison Committee, the unofficial grouping of North
Sea oil workers, said last night it had been given official recognition as a
trade union.
The recognition, by the government's trade-union certification officer, will
further inflame relations between the committee and other established trade
unions, including the AEU engineering union.
The OILC, led by Mr Ronnie McDonald, was behind the industrial unrest on oil
platforms in the summer of 1990. Mr McDonald described the listing of the
OILC as a trade union as a 'watershed'. It would clarify the authority of
the body at industrial tribunals, for example.
A certificate of independence would be required before the new union could
claim back money spent on balloting, however. Mr McDonald said the group
hoped for a certificate of independence soon.
The OILC hopes to recruit a 'viable operational base' of 3,000 members
within its first year.
Mr McDonald said the new union wanted to affiliate to the Scottish Trades
Union Congress. The long-term aim would be for affiliation to the TUC
itself.
</TEXT>
