FT  12 FEB 92 / US pledge on role in Europe's defence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US yesterday assured Britain that its military commitment to Europe's
defence would not be affected by disagreements with the European Community
in the Gatt trade liberalisation talks.
Both President George Bush in Washington and Vice-President Dan Quayle, who
had talks in London yesterday with British leaders, stressed there was no
connection between the issues.
Mr John Major, the UK prime minister, said after dinner last night with Mr
Quayle that they had discussed the 'absolutely imperative importance in
making sure the round is completed and completed successfully and as
speedily as possible'.
The confusion about US policy arose out of remarks made by Mr Quayle in
Munich last weekend, when he appeared to establish some kind of linkage
between the Gatt talks and the US military presence in Europe. He later
denied that had been his intention.
In talks yesterday with Mr Douglas Hurd he left the British foreign
secretary in no doubt about the strength of the US military commitment, but
officials declined to say how large it would be. The US is widely believed
to be planning to cut its troop strength to below 100,000.
