<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / Guinness trial collapses: Judge urges radical solution to
problems of serious fraud cases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, ROBERT RICE and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SECOND Guinness trial collapsed yesterday with calls for a radical
solution to the problems of long fraud cases and widespread concern in the
House of Commons about the cost to the taxpayer.
Mr Justice Henry, the judge in all four trials arising out of the 1986
Guinness takeover of Distillers, discharged the jury because of serious
concern over the mental and emotional health of Mr Roger Seelig, former
merchant banker.
He told the jury: 'Once again this case has thrown up the problems of long
criminal trials and the appropriateness of our criminal justice system -
whose rules were designed to cater for short trials and simple facts - to
such long and complex trials.
'It seems to me inevitable that we must find a cheaper and quicker way to
deal with serious fraud trials, and the likelihood is we shall need a
radical solution rather than merely tinkering with procedures.'
On Friday the Serious Fraud Office announced it had dropped charges against
Mr Seelig and Mr David Mayhew, a partner in broker Cazenove, who were to
have stood trial in the third Guinness case.
The jury at Southwark Crown Court heard that the strain on Mr Seelig had
reached a point where 'it is no longer possible for him to conduct his
defence adequately'.
The view of two psychiatrists was that continuation might lead to Mr Seelig
'doing something irrevocable'. In the circumstances it would not be right to
continue the trial against Lord Spens, Mr Seelig's co-defendant, the judge
said.
He said the SFO could have a week in which to consider its position in
relation to the case. It is almost inconceivable that Mr Seelig will be
required to face another trial. The position of Lord Spens is more doubtful.
Mr Justice Henry's call for changes in criminal trial procedures was echoed
by Lord Roskill, the former Law Lord who chaired the 1986 inquiry into fraud
trials.
Lord Roskill said the government had been wrong to ignore his advice that
complex and lengthy fraud cases were unsuitable for jury trial. He believed
such cases should be tried instead by a special tribunal comprising a judge
and two lay members with experience of business and finance.
The Blue Arrow case, in which verdicts on the remaining five defendants are
imminent, is likely to be subjected to a critical post mortem.
News of the collapse of the second Guinness trial brought concern from both
sides of the Commons about the costs of the case, and Labour calls for a
review of the way serious fraud cases are handled.
Ms Marjorie Mowlam, Labour's City spokeswoman, said the trial represented
'an appalling waste of public money'. It was, she said, no good just blaming
the SFO. There had to be 'a review of the law to include civil as well as
criminal penalties in frauds of this size'.
'Guinness was a major financial scandal, and for this to be the outcome
makes a mockery of dealing with fraud in the City of London,' she said,
calling on Mr John Redwood, the corporate affairs minister, to make a
statement.
Mr Kenneth Warren, the Tory chairman of the all-party committee on trade and
industry, described it as 'a ridiculously appalling waste of time and
money'.
'I trust that now the lessons learnt from these cases and the experience of
the regulatory organisations will provide security against such problems
arising,' he said.
The climax of prosecutions arising from three big City scandals of the 1980s
have resulted in mixed fortunes for the SFO. The 10-year sentence imposed on
Mr Peter Clowes in the Barlow Clowes trial is the one unambiguous feather in
the SFO's cap.
Mr Seelig, a former Morgan Grenfell corporate finance director, and Lord
Spens, former corporate finance managing director at the Henry Ansbacher
merchant bank, denied fraud and false accounting charges arising from a
share support operation mounted by Guinness during its Pounds 2.7bn takeover
of Distillers in 1986.
Mr Ernest Saunders, the former Guinness chief who served 10 months in jail
over the Guinness affair, said yesterday that in the light of what had
happened in the second and third trials he would discuss with his lawyers
'what steps can be taken to help me establish my innocence'.
Seeling Interview, Page 8
Justice the loser, Page 8
Editorial comment, Page 16
Roskill's call, Page 17
</TEXT>
