<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / Appointments: Manufacturer for small chair
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
After just three weeks in the family catering and bakery business Richard
Brucciani decided he had had enough and went off to run a small offshoot
importing the paper hats worn by staff in fast-food outlets.
Twenty one years later Pal International has grown to turnover of Pounds 9m
and a workforce of 180 making hygiene products for the catering, industrial
and healthcare markets. Pal's success and sterling work in the CBI's East
Midland region have propelled Brucciani, aged 46, into the post of chairman
of the CBI's Smaller Firms Council.
This is an important job because it helps establish the CBI's credentials as
a representative of small business - though many outsiders find it hard to
believe that the organisation's big company members, who pay most of its
bills, do not still call the shots.
Brucciani, whose grand-father came to England in the 1860s, says he did not
leave the family firm because of a disagreement but because he realised
retailing was not for him. He quickly moved Pal into manufacturing and has
fac-tories in Malta, Paris and Burnley as well as his headquarters in Oadby,
Leicestershire. Pal has come through the recession well, meeting its 20 per
cent annual profit growth target; this is because 45 per cent of sales are
overseas and because food processing hygiene is an expanding market,
Brucciani says.
He believes the British do themselves down when they say they are not good
at manufacturing; they are actually quite good but don't encourage their
best people to go into it.
A keen amateur pilot and 'unskilled' but enthusiastic violin player,
Brucciani has two years in which to put his message across.
</TEXT>
