<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / International Company News: Banque Bruxelles in talks with
insurance companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL and RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BANQUE Bruxelles Lambert, Belgium's second largest bank, is negotiating an
agreement with two shareholders on insurance products. A co-operative deal
between BBL and the shareholders could squeeze out a counter-proposal from
Internationale Nederlanden Groep (ING), the Dutch banking and insurance
group.
ING, which owns 5.9 per cent of BBL through a Belgian subsidiary, was at the
centre of press speculation last year that it was poised to launch a paper
and cash bid for BBL which would have cost the Dutch company the equivalent
of more than Fl 3bn (Dollars 1.65bn). It declined to comment on the reports
at the time.
Responding to Belgian press reports yesterday, BBL said talks with two
insurance companies - Royale Belge, 47 per cent of which is owned by Union
des Assurances de Paris, and Winterthur of Switzerland - were
'well-advanced', and could involve 'very limited' movements of shares. UAP
controls 9.35 per cent of BBL, and Winterthur 4.8 per cent.
The bank played down the significance of the talks. 'It's quite normal that
we should want to sell insurance products and that we should discuss this
with shareholders,' the Belgian bank said.
ING countered by saying that its proposal would enable all the various
insurers who own a stake in BBL to participate in a partnership, with the
exact level of involvement determined by the size of their shareholdings.
The Royale Belge-Winterthur proposal, by contrast, would exclude all other
BBL shareholders, including ING, which is keen to bolster its presence
around Europe.
ING also confirmed that last week it had informally raised the possibility
of arriving at some form of co-operation in banking to BBL.
It denied that these talks centred on ING expanding its stake in BBL.
</TEXT>
