<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / International Company News: Ericsson slumps to SKr1.6bn on
flat sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ERICSSON, the Swedish telecommunications group, yesterday said a combination
of weak demand and restructuring provisions had pushed pre-tax profits for
1991 down by two-thirds to SKr1.6bn (Dollars 274.4m).
Ericsson warned that demand for telecommunication products would continue to
be 'very weak' during the first half of this year, mainly because of planned
cuts in capital expenditure by telephone operating companies.
It added that the 1992 profit figure - which was 'highly dependent upon
sensitivity to economic conditions' - was expected to be low.
Orders last year fell by 9 per cent to SKr44.7bn, while sales were virtually
unchanged at SKr45.8bn, against SKr45.7bn in 1990. Fully diluted, earnings
per shares dropped from SKr14.66. However, Ericsson is holding its dividend
at SKr3.50.
While order bookings increased by 26 per cent during the fourth quarter of
last year to SKr13.82bn, the group's pre-tax profit for the period fell by
97 per cent to SKr93m.
However, the final three months showed a significant recovery over the
third-quarter performance, which left the company facing a SKr194m loss.
Mr Lars Ramqvist, chief executive, said the company intended to continue
with its investment development plans despite the recession. He insisted
that 'strong development programmes coupled with cost effectiveness' were
enabling the company to maintain and strengthen its international market
shares.
When the economy begins to recover, Mr Ramqvist added, the company would
return to a 'good level of profitability'.
Part of last year's profit decline is due to the SKr600m being set aside by
the company for its continuing restructuring. Last week, it announced that
1,000 jobs were to go mainly at its Swedish operations, where 14,000 are
employed.
</TEXT>
