<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / UK Company News: Manchester Ship lifts operating profit 23%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANCHESTER Ship Canal reported a 48 per cent fall in annual profits as an
improvement in port operations along the 36-mile canal failed to offset an
85 per cent drop in income from exceptional property dealings.
Pre-tax profits for 1991 amounted to Pounds 10.8m (Pounds 20.7m), but the
previous year's results included nearly Pounds 12m of exceptional net income
from the sale of canalside land near Warrington for waste disposal.
Port operating profit expanded 23 per cent to Pounds 5.25m (Pounds 4.27m) on
turnover almost unchanged at Pounds 20.2m (Pounds 19.8m) and less tonnage
handled.
Mr Robert Hough, chairman, described the results as 'very satisfactory'
because profits before exceptional income and expenditure were a record
Pounds 9.62m (Pounds 9.55m). With property income only marginally up at
Pounds 4.65m, investment income 38 per cent down at Pounds 1.43m and
interest charges higher, the improvement came from better port operations,
where staffing costs and operating charges have been reduced by 27 per cent
in four years.
About two thirds of the company's shares are now owned by Peel Holdings,
whose chairman, Mr John Whittaker, took control of the canal through a
private company after a bitter takeover battle in 1987.
Mr Whittaker's original policy was to plough back all profits, but
Manchester Ship eventually returned to the dividend list last year. The
dividend is unchanged at 4.5p.
