<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Public understanding of Aids has been thwarted by the determination of so
many campaigners to pursue political correctness rather than truth. If it is
thought the facts may offend homosexuals or black Africans then everything
is done to suppress the facts. Most recently desperate efforts have been
made to conceal the latest figures concerning heterosexual Aids in Britain
because those figures do not support the apocalyptic predictions of 1990 and
1991.
On the contrary, they show that heterosexuals with the disease are still
limited almost exclusively to those who have had sexual relationships with
drug abusers, homosexuals and sub-Saharan Africans.
One public information source with a good record of thinking for itself on
this is Dispatches where two previous programmes made by Joan Shenton have
questioned the received wisdom.
Today's edition (9.00 C4) queries the efficacy of AZT, the main drug so far
prescribed for the treatment of Aids.
BBC1 begins a new series of QED with an international competition among
engineering students to build waste collecting machines from junk (9.40).
</TEXT>
