<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 92 / Action by Lloyd's Names: Expression of relief as settlement
is achieved - Pounds 116m Outhwaite settlement is significant triumph for
those who acted to recover heavy losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NAMES WHO joined Mr Peter Nutting in taking action against Outhwaite joined
yesterday in praising his role and the financial relief the settlement would
provide.
But many did not want to talk publicly about the arrangement. 'When all's
said and done it has been a very personal and painful experience,' said one
Name who wanted to remain anonymous yesterday. 'I'm just pleased it is all
over.'
Mr Robert Williams, a businessman with a Pounds 60,000 share of the
syndicate's income, against which he estimates he has already paid out
Pounds 280,000, said: 'My first impression is that the settlement is very
good. I will certainly be buying a magnum of champagne.
'My reaction is one of extreme pleasure and gratitude to Mr Nutting. Nobody
else took the slightest interest in our plight.'
Since he joined as a Name in 1973 he had expected an average return of about
10 per cent over the years. 'Outhwaite was a catastrophe far beyond anything
that had happened.
'For the last five years I have been waking up with a cloud over my head and
thinking I'll be bankrupted. There is no price you can put on the extreme
pain and suffering I suffered. It was like a creeping paralysis. I had to
sell my business, cash in my life insurance and borrow large sums.'
But he struck a note of caution about the decision. 'The big unknown is the
quantity of future losses. Until it is all capped one has to be very
cautious.'
Other Names were worried about the fact that Mr Outhwaite has still not been
able to close the 1982 underwriting year and that claims could continue to
come in. 'This is still a running sore,' added another Name.
Mr Geoffrey McLean sold his construction company to Tarmac in the 1970s and
invested some of the proceeds in becoming a Name. In spite of being one of
the beneficiaries of the settlement, he regrets that decision.
With a Pounds 25,000 line on Outhwaite he stands to recover more than Pounds
100,000 to set against losses incurred more recently.
'As the affair unfolded we could see we couldn't lose - the risks were
stupid. The idea of insurance is to spread the risk. Outhwaite concentrated
it.'
But the affair has 'soured his faith' in Lloyd's. 'I suppose I joined
because of a bit of greed, maybe something to do with the cachet. I'd have
been better off without it.'
</TEXT>
