FT  11 FEB 92 / International Company News: Mitsui to invest in new US film
group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN, REUTER and AP-DJ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MITSUI, the Japanese trading company, has joined forces with a group of
investors, including a fund controlled by the Pritzker family of Chicago, to
invest an initial Dollars 100m in Savoy Pictures, a new film distribution
company, writes Alan Friedman in New York.
Among the investors and managers of Savoy Pictures will be Mr Victor
Kaufman, former chief executive of Columbia Pictures, and Mr Lewis Korman,
former chief operating officer of Columbia. Both left Columbia after it was
acquired in 1989 by Sony of Japan.
Savoy is Mitsui's first investment in the US film industry, but the Japanese
company is a minority investor. The largest single equity stake is held by
GKH, an investment fund controlled by Mr Jay Pritzker. Also investing is
Allen &amp; Company, the investment boutique, and Mr Andy Vajna, one of the
founders of Carolco Pictures, the independent film company.
Mr Korman said Savoy's aim would be to distribute around 15 films a year by
1995. He said Savoy would also help film-makers to arrange finance.
*****
CONRAIL, the US railroad, has turned in a fourth-quarter loss of Dollars
376m or Dollars 9.23 a share, after providing for an after-tax charge of
Dollars 447m covering costs of asset reductions, Reuter reports.
This leaves the group with a net loss for the year of Dollars 207m or
Dollars 3.59. For the previous year Conrail earned a profit of Dollars 247m
or Dollars 5.10 a share, with Dollars 76m or Dollars 1.78 coming in the
fourth quarter. Revenues for the latest fourth quarter were Dollars 847m
against Dollars 841m and for the year totalled Dollars 3.25bn against
Dollars 3.37bn.
*****
NCR, a unit of American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, has entered a comprehensive
alliance with Electronic Data Systems (EDS), an offshoot of General Motors,
AP-DJ reports. EDS will provide systems integration consulting and services
to the commercial marketplace using NCR's enterprise-wide computing systems.
