<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / Sharp response to Quayle on trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER, FRANCES WILLIAMS and ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, GENEVA, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE WARNING by Mr Dan Quayle, US vice-president, that a failure to conclude
the Uruguay Round trade talks could fuel protectionism in the US and
encourage those wanting to pull all US troops out of Nato, drew a sharp
response yesterday from European Community agriculture ministers.
The reaction came as Mr Quayle said his remarks had been misinterpreted.
The agriculture ministers were meeting in Brussels to discuss plans to
reform the EC's Common Agricultural Policy and farm subsidy reductions
within the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade liberalisation
negotiations - the main obstacle to conclusion of the Round.
Mr John Gummer, UK agriculture minister, said: 'There's been too much of
this megaphone diplomacy. This kind of behaviour is not very helpful. There
is a lot at stake, in a sensitive negotiation, which has to be between equal
partners.' He added that 'no doubt it was something he (Mr Quayle) was not
properly briefed on'.
The UK is among the minority of member states having little difficulty with
the farm subsidies formula drawn up by Gatt in December, which the EC as a
whole is seeking to renegotiate.
France has led efforts to limit the degree of liberalisation in farm trade
sought by Gatt, whereas most of its partners want amendments to make the
subsidy cuts compatible with EC farm reform.
Mr Quayle's damage limitation exercise was undertaken at a news conference
in Geneva. He denied any specific linkage between a breakdown of the Gatt
talks and US troop levels in Europe, but he stressed that there was
inevitably a link between economic and military security.
The US vice-president sought to distance himself from more forthright
remarks by other prominent US participants at an international defence
conference in Munich on Sunday, who underlined the military consequences for
Europe of a failure in the Gatt talks.
Stressing that he wanted to correct a 'misimpression', Mr Quayle said that,
unlike the other speakers at the Munich seminar, he was speaking for
President George Bush and the US administration when he said there was no
linkage between the Gatt talks and US troop levels in Europe.
However, he followed up these soothing words with an another stern warning
that a breakdown of the Uruguay Round of trade talks could trigger 'mindless
spending' on subsidies, which the US would feel obliged to match. 'The US
will certainly meet any subsidies with an in-kind response,' he said.
</TEXT>
