FT  11 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: GP fund-holding producing benefits
for patients
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   A REPORT yesterday suggested that GP fund-holding
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
one of the most controversial aspects of the government's health reforms -
is producing benefits for patients, Alan Pike writes.
Professor Howard Glennerster of the London School of Economics, who produced
the report for the King's Fund Institute, the health policy research centre,
admitted he had started the project as a 'sceptic about fund-holding'.
However, his research had made him 'far more positive about the
opportunities it presents'.
Under fund-holding some family doctors hold budgets from which they purchase
care for their patients.
Prof Glennerster says he is not yet in a position to judge whether
fund-holding should be extended universally, and adds that weaknesses in the
scheme need to be addressed. For example budgets should be set in ways which
do not penalise GPs who care for disproportionate large numbers of the very
sick and old or work in disadvantaged areas.
</TEXT>
