<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday spelled out the case for Scotland staying within the union
with England and Wales by outlining its definition of 'the maximum autonomy'
feasible without severing the links of nearly three centuries, Ivo Dawnay
writes.
Mr Gordon Brown, shadow trade and industry secretary, said there was no
advantage in 'breaking the first internal market that Europe achieved' when
the European Community was working towards common economic goals.
He said the demands of the Scottish National party for a separate currency
and exchange rates represented 'the costly trappings and not the essential
substance of a modern national identity'.
He went on to attack the Conservatives for gambling with the union by
attempting to 'polarise the debate' between the status quo and separatism.
Mrs Margaret Ewing, SNP MP for Moray, said last night in a party political
broadcast that Labour's programme was simply a 'prospectus for continued
poverty and economic stagnation' in Scotland.
Observer, Page 18
*****
NORTHERN IRELAND: The government's majority slumped to three in the Commons
last night when an order extending trade union legislation already operating
in Britain to Northern Ireland was passed by 90 votes to 87.
Ministers and their handful of supporters in the almost deserted chamber
ignored shouts of 'resign' from the few Labour MPs present to hear the
result.
*****
BRITISH RAIL: The government would be reluctant to tolerate increases in the
sums paid by BR in compensation once the new passengers' charter comes into
effect, Mr Roger Freeman, transport minister, suggested yesterday.
The government had 'no plans to be associated with' any scheme that would
involve significant costs, he said. The 'sensible' way of improving services
would be to create performance targets for BR.
*****
OIL RIG SAFETY: Mr Michael Howard, employment secretary has promised to
consider amending a private member's bill now in the Lords to include
legislation to protect from victimisation by employers workers on North Sea
oil rigs who complain about the inadequacy of safety arrangements.
