<DATE>920211
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics (Campaign Profile): Ashdown's Bonnie
Prince Charlie
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHORTLY after the 1983 general election the boyish Social Democratic Party
MP for Ross, Cromarty and Skye dashed from the Commons chamber, anxiously
seeking the advice of a colleague.
He was supposed to be replying for the party in a complex debate on the
Scottish rate support grant. He turned to his ally and confessed: 'I have
never paid rates in my life.'
Mr Charles Kennedy, now president of the Liberal Democrats, still suffers
from having responsibility thrust upon him at an early age. Just 32 years
old, he has been an MP for almost a decade. With his pillow-like face and
deep-set eyes, neat streak of glowing red hair and a reputation as
Westminster's most likeable chap, he will take a leading role in the Liberal
Democrats' election campaign, touring constituencies and providing
television 'sound bites'.
Not too high a profile, however, because Mr Kennedy has yet to show that a
bonnie prince can be a powerful Liberal Democrat force, perhaps a future
leader.
He has still to demonstrate full mastery of policy details and prove he can
be a philosopher king, even in a minority party unlikely to see much
increase in the election from its current 22 MPs. For now, Mr Paddy Ashdown,
party leader, sets the Liberal Democrat vision; Mr Des Wilson is the
election strategist.
Mr Kennedy's colleagues are almost as disappointed by his lack of
application as they are smitten by his human warmth.
He is a bon viveur, a wit, a charmer who always has time for everyone. He is
someone with an urgency to get on with enjoying life, for whom a good joke
can save a thousand policy lapses. 'He is the Prince Hal of the party,' says
one senior official. 'He is still at the wine-and-song stage.'
Mr Kennedy knows his biggest skill is as a communicator, rather than
championing his social market politics. 'He has never made any pretence of
being the party intellectual or thinker,' says one Liberal Democrat MP.
Another says: 'He has kept it in check since he became president, but he did
have a tendency to be flippant at the party's expense.'
But there is a borderline between communicating as a politician and as a
journalist which Mr Kennedy sometimes fudges. Since winning the party
presidency two years ago, he has appeared less as the party clown. But he
still broadcasts regularly on radio for BBC Scotland and London's LBC. He
also writes a column for The Scotsman. Few doubt he could make his money
from professional punditry.
Liberal Democrats have a hard time grabbing prime time in the Commons'
chamber. But Mr Kennedy does not compensate with the press conferences or
campaign launches beloved by his more ambitious colleagues - even though he
is a spokesman on health, one of the biggest election issues. It is as if he
would prefer to be on the other side, asking the questions and calling the
shots.
Inquiries at the Liberal Democrats' Westminster office for speeches on Mr
Kennedy's political philosophy suggest that his reputation as a wag
predominates. 'Are you looking for the sense-of-humour line?' asks the press
officer.
In fact Mr Kennedy openly admits that his conversion, first to social
democracy and then to the Liberal Democrats, 'was not a great conversion on
the road to Damascus sort of thing'. As a teenager his sympathies were
'fairly moderate, sort of centre-right of the Labour party', but his
greatest enthusiasm was debating.
In Fort William, where he was born, he won a Scottish schools' debating
competition. He loved the clash of arguments and inventive interlocution. At
Glasgow University he decided against joining the Labour club when he
discovered that it was gripped by an aversion to all things elitist and did
not take part in the debating society.
Instead he turned to the new Social Democratic Party - and particularly its
founder member, Mr Roy Jenkins, now Lord Jenkins of Hillhead.
He joined the SDP team which won the Glasgow Hillhead by-election. A year
later, while studying in the US at Indiana University he applied to be SDP
candidate in the geographically vast Ross, Cromarty and Skye constituency.
He was surprised to be selected, and more aghast when he beat the sitting
Tory MP with a majority of 1,704.
After the 1987 election, he was the most eager of the five SDP MPs to merge
with the Liberals.
Lord Jenkins remains a mentor. Mr Kennedy's political philosophy, as far as
it goes, mixes social market economics and quotations on liberty from John
Stuart Mill with Lord Jenkins' warnings on the tyranny of the current
political system. Like all Liberal Democrats, Mr Kennedy wants proportional
representation for elections. But he is pragmatic, rather than passionate.
He is a Catholic but not fanatically religious.
He has a high regard for Sir David Steel, former Liberal leader, who saw
politics more as a vehicle for achieving influence, less about the power of
ideas.
In that he differs from the radicalism of Mr Ashdown, who has set a sweeping
Liberal Democrat agenda - pro-Europe, internationalist, anti-monopoly, and
strong on individuals' rights, education and the environment.
So far there is no evidence of friction between Mr Ashdown and Mr Kennedy.
The roles they have carved are mutually exclusive. Mr Ashdown leads
aggressively from the front, expecting his colleagues to follow. Mr Kennedy
is happy to share the bandwagon if it is going roughly in the direction he
wants. He works hard on the 'rubber chicken' circuit - the endless
constituency annual general meetings and after-dinner speeches.
Where the clash with Mr Ashdown might come is if the Liberal Democrats held
the balance of power after the general election. As much as Mr Ashdown has
gingered up the party's radicalism, so he has also ratcheted up the
conditions for his support. He is determined to force constitutional reform
and an agreed agenda for a four-year government.
Mr Kennedy is perhaps less ambitious. He was a supporter of the 1977-78
Lib-Lab pact which saw the Liberals gain little in terms of policies
implemented. On his own, he might settle for less than Mr Ashdown. A
devolved assembly for Scotland might be enough.
Yet maybe rebellion is too much to expect of Mr Kennedy; he shows little
inclination to rock the boat, he is in no hurry for power. His strong
following among Liberal Democrats would make him a popular choice in the
party to succeed Mr Ashdown. But he may want to learn a little more about
rigour and ruthlessness in politics first.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9 Illustration (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-9581</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CBKBQAENFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920211
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Lib Dems step up pact demands -
Hung Parliament
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIBERAL Democrats would press for at least one cabinet post if they formed a
pact with either Labour or the Tories in a hung parliament.
Party strategists have decided that the conditions they have set already for
a post-election deal - legislation to introduce proportional representation
and agreement on a four-year programme of government - would require Liberal
Democrats holding ministerial office.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, Liberal Democrat leader, will step up his party's campaign
for constitutional reform today with a policy launch combining proposals on
electoral systems, a bill of rights and Scottish devolution.
He has previously said a bill on proportional representation would be a
prerequisite for any pact agreement, but has so far stopped short of
insisting on a cabinet post. Senior Liberal Democrats confirmed, however,
that they are determined that any pact must yield tangible gains for the
party if their support among voters is not to be jeopardised.
The lesson learnt from the 1977-78 Lib-Lab pact, when the then Liberal party
sustained the Labour government of Mr James Callaghan but failed to will
many policy changes, is that negotiations will have to be far tougher.
Liberal Democrats would have to be subject to the disciplines of government
office and have the same access to information and advice as their larger
coalition partners. In the 1977-78 pact, Liberal MPs often felt
outmanoeuvred by Labour ministers backed by civil servants.
There appears to be no preference among Liberal Democrats for heading any
particular department - although offers of a cabinet post without portfolio
would probably be rejected as meaningless. The home secretary's job might be
a possibility if it was overseeing constitutional reform.
Liberal Democrats yesterday previewed a general election poster with the
slogan: 'No wonder Britain's ill, it has a bad constitution.' It is the
first part of a week-long 'good government' campaign.
Later, the party revived a campaign dating back to the Lib-Lab pact for
proportional representation in elections to the European parliament.
This week the party will take the European parliament to the European Court
of Justice for failing to initiate electoral reform in the EC.
Mr Andrew Duff, legal campaign leader, said he wanted the court to force the
EC to start a reform process in time for the 1994 European elections: 'If
the European Community has not helped to modernise Britain's electoral
system by then, the European parliament will be a joke.'
Sir Russell Johnston, Liberal Democrat EC spokesman, said: 'It is scandalous
that British Liberal Democrats, who form the largest Liberal party in
Europe, have been excluded from the European parliament by the perverse and
reactionary nature of 'first-past-the-post'.'
</TEXT>
