FT  11 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Hattersley hints on top rate -
Taxation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR provided a further clue to its plans for a 50 per cent tax band
yesterday when Mr Roy Hattersley, the deputy leader, said that people
earning less than Pounds 36,000 a year would not have to pay the top rate.
Mr Hattersley, speaking on LBC radio, said that people would be willing to
pay more tax to finance higher pensions and child benefit.
Mr John Smith, the shadow chancellor, has repeatedly said that an incoming
Labour chancellor would need flexibility in drawing up his Budget plans, and
has refused to be drawn on exactly where the 50 per cent band would apply.
Labour has emphasised, however, that the top rate would affect only those
earning 'well over Pounds 30,000'.
Party officials said that Mr Hattersley's remarks were no more than an
amplification of this line, and that he was giving merely indicative
figures.
His comments were seized on by the Tories as evidence of Labour confusion.
Mr David Mellor, chief secretary to the Treasury, said: 'Roy Hattersley has
shown once again that he does not trust John Smith to shape Labour's
economic policy.' He added: 'The trouble for Labour's split and splinted
economic team is that people will remember the lessons of history.'
