<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / The Blue Arrow Trial: Warning to jury on verdicts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE JURY in the Blue Arrow fraud trial will today retire to consider their
verdicts - exactly one year to the day after court proceedings began.
Completing his summing-up yesterday, Mr Justice McKinnon, the judge,
repeatedly warned the 11 men and one woman not to convict the five remaining
defendants if unsure of their guilt.
He said the prosecution's remaining allegation was that in agreeing to buy
shares in the 1987 rights issue after the passing of the official deadline -
so increasing the take-up level from 38 per cent to 48 per cent - the
defendants had conspired to dishonestly mislead the markets.
When summing up the evidence against four of the defendants, the judge
listed a series of tests in each case. Unless these tests had been met by
the prosecution, the jury had to acquit, he said.
The case against Mr Jonathan Cohen, County NatWest's former chief executive,
depended on whether, in a telephone call to Mr David Reed, County's former
corporate finance head, he had been told of and approved the 'late take-up'
before the shares were bought. In his evidence, Mr Reed, another defendant,
had denied telling Mr Cohen of this.
Mr Nicholas Wells, a former County director, had given evidence that he had
thought the late take-up was both legal and against nobody's interests. Mr
Wells' approach to both the Bank of England and his superiors might be
thought positive points in his favour, the judge continued.
Mr Martin Gibbs, a former head of corporate finance at Phillips &amp; Drew
Securities, had checked whether the late take-up was legal and obtained
authority from his chairman, Mr Bryce Cottrell.
The jury would want to bear both points in mind in deciding Mr Gibbs'
honesty, he said.
Mr Christopher Stainforth, a former P&amp;D director, should be compared with Mr
David Roper, another corporate financier present at the meeting when the
shares were bought. Both had relied on the late take-up being approved by
their superiors and the prosecution had not sug-gested Mr Roper was a
conspirator.
'Is not Mr Stainforth's position identical to Mr Roper's?' the judge said.
If the jury felt there was no difference between the position of the two men
they might feel no alternative but to acquit Mr Stainforth, he continued.
</TEXT>
