<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / The Barlow Clowes Trial: North relieved as a scandal becomes
history
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FINANCIAL and prof-essional-services sectors of Manchester and Leeds
appear to have escaped any taint from the Barlow Clowes affair, although
some within their business communities had an uncomfortable brush with the
scandal.
In Leeds several leading professionals have made a point since the Barlow
Clowes collapse of briefing existing and potential clients on the background
to the affair.
In Manchester, respectable professionals were so suspicious of Mr Clowes'
bond-washing operations - and the high levels of commission he was
understood to have offered some intermediaries - that they had nothing to do
with him from the outset in the 1970s.
With Manchester's finance sector mainly contained in what the city calls its
'square half-mile', professional networks consigned Mr Clowes to the fringe.
When the scandal broke in 1988 many Manchester professionals could honestly
claim never to have heard of him.
His Manchester professional origins were as a fairly lowly life-assurance
salesman. Barlow Clowes itself operated 10 miles out of the city in Poynton,
Cheshire. From it Mr Clowes sold his investment schemes through the then
poorly regulated financial intermediaries.
But by the time Leeds professionals became involved in 1987, Barlow Clowes
was a big business which Mr Clowes wanted to reverse into James Ferguson
Holdings - a quoted but formerly moribund loss-maker that had started life
in knitwear - in order to go public and achieve respectability.
In 1985 Mr Cramer, a young Leeds market trader, had bought into Ferguson to
raise capital for expansion into financial services and property. Meanwhile
Mr Clowes needed to find other means to keep up the returns he had promised
investors after the Inland Revenue closed the tax loophole through which
Barlow Clowes made its gilts operations pay.
This had worked by selling gilts just before they matured to obtain capital
gains which were then taxed at a lower rate than the interest on the bonds.
A quoted company offered a vehicle for building a network of investment
activity.
The Leeds financial community organised a rights issue so the company could
expand and incorporate the Barlow Clowes businesses. The professionals
involved in the local community took Mr Clowes on trust as they knew his
associate, Mr Guy Cramer.
Rensburg, which has since become part of the BWD Rensburg quoted financial
services group, was the main underwriter to the rights issue and informed
the Stock Exchange that it had been misled over the status of the
sub-underwriter, which turned out to be under the control of Mr Clowes.
Investigations by the Stock Exchange, the Department of Trade and Industry
and the Serious Fraud Office exonerated Rensburg, which had acted in good
faith. Coincidentally, the Barlow Clowes house of cards started to collapse
soon after Rensburg's resignation.
There was some trepidation in Leeds in case negligence claims arose against
rights-issue advisers after James Ferguson's collapse. The fears proved
groundless, but many in the business community of the north will be glad to
see the end of the Barlow Clowes affair.
</TEXT>
