<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / The Barlow Clowes Trial: A landmark case of old-fashioned
theft - Two of the four defendants are found guilty Crash has cost British
taxpayers over Pounds 150m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON and RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COLLAPSE of Barlow Clowes was a landmark for the UK investment world of
the 1980s.
While insider trading and stock market manipulation had become known as the
fashionable ills of the age, Mr Peter Clowes' little-known investment
management business from the north-west was busy perpetrating a more
old-fashioned form of financial wrongdoing: theft.
Investors' money was used to provide Mr Clowes with an extravagant
lifestyle, according to the prosecution case mounted by the Serious Fraud
Office. New investments were taken in and used to pay 'returns' to existing
investors in a constant recycling of money. It worked as long as new cash
was available to feed the machine - a classic 'ponzi' scheme, one of the
oldest forms of investment fraud.
The case proved a watershed for the UK's system of financial regulation, for
the public's confidence in investment firms, and, above all, for the
strongly non-interventionist government of Mrs Margaret Thatcher.
Despite strong denials of any responsibility by the Department of Trade and
Industry, which had been responsible for regulating the firm for many years,
the government bowed to an unprecedented campaign mounted by Barlow Clowes'
11,000 mainly elderly investors.
Attempts to launch a City 'lifeboat' to bail out Barlow Clowes' hapless
investors were initially rejected by a financial establishment unwilling to
admit Mr Clowes as one of its own. About 500 elderly investors had already
died by the time Mr Nicholas Ridley, then trade and industry secretary, gave
way to pressure to pay out compensation.
The announcement of the pay-out coincided with the publication of a report
by the ombudsman, which criticised the DTI on five counts of
maladministration regarding the licensing and regulation of Barlow Clowes.
The case has so far cost British taxpayers more than Pounds 150m. In its
attempts to recover some of this money, the DTI has already issued more than
800 writs.
The accountancy firms Touche Ross and Spicer &amp; Pegler (which has since
merged with Touche), the four biggest UK clearing banks - and a number of
investment advisers who put money into Barlow Clowes - may all be sued to
recover the taxpayer's money. So far only Pounds 550,000 has been recovered
 -after a successful action against an adviser, ACD Miller.
At the start of the trial last summer, the jury was told that the Barlow
Clowes fraud was massive, flagrant and 'as old as the hills' in style.
According to Mr Alan Suckling QC, bringing the prosecution for the SFO,
investors were persuaded that their money would be securely invested in
gilts, when in reality it was spent on 'living the life of Riley'.
Showing the jurors a photograph of Mr Clowes's yacht - formerly owned by
Christina Onassis - he told them: 'If you look carefully you will see the
only gilt-edged object bought with investors' money by Mr Clowes. Can you
guess what it is? The taps'.
One of the last things investors thought their money would be spent on was
the chateau and vineyard near Bordeaux bought for Pounds 600,000, he said.
As he listed other ways that clients' money had been spent - on luxury cars
and funding corporate raids - Mr Suckling's style was to let the facts speak
for themselves, underlining his points with only a tone of dry irony.
The jury was presented with a detailed account of how the fraud operated.
The company's brochures stated that clients' money would be invested in
gilt-edged stock - a crucial selling point for those anxious to find a
secure place to invest their life savings.
However, contracts contained clauses authorising non-gilts investments
which, Mr Clowes was to maintain, enabled his company to adopt an
'alternative investment strategy'. This strategy, far from being based on
gilts, saw Barlow Clowes operating as a mini merchant bank and funding
take-over bids for public and private companies it wanted to control.
Between 1983 and 1987 more than Pounds 113m of the funds invested in the
offshore companies and partnerships in the Barlow Clowes fund management
empire were milked from investors, Mr Suckling said.
At the end of 1987, when DTI inspectors began investigating, strenuous
efforts were made to throw them off the track. Documents were shredded,
bogus letters were placed on files to indicate accounts had been closed and
Pounds 16m of clients' funds were used to plug holes in the accounts.
When the firm collapsed in May 1988 the true position emerged. More than
Pounds 225m had been invested by clients and a Pounds 115m liability to them
remained. Only Pounds 1.9m was found invested in gilts. The value of other
assets discovered by the receivers and liquidators totalled Pounds 60m.
Otherwise, the cupboard was bare.
Mr Clowes had been 'the instigator and driving force' behind the fraud, the
prosecution said. Mr Peter Naylor, a computer consultant, had been his
'lieutenant' in helping milk investors' funds.
Over the course of the 109-day trial, 113 witnesses gave evidence. These
included a succession of investors who recounted why, attracted by the
security of gilts, they had put their money into Barlow Clowes.
One, who had invested Pounds 440,000, said she had done so because she
understood that her savings would be 'as safe as the Bank of England'.
Only two of the defendants - Mr Clowes and Mr Naylor - opted to go into the
witness box to give evidence.
Mr Clowes admitted very few gilts had been bought. He agreed that although
the group billed itself as a gilts specialist it in fact acted as a mini
merchant bank. However, he repeatedly denied that his dealings had been
dishonest. The clauses in his company's contracts allowing other investments
meant his conduct had been 'absolutely honest', he insisted.
The complex arrangements for handling investors' funds were not a laundering
operation, as the prosecution suggested, but a means of maintaining clients'
confidentiality, he told the court.
Summing up, Mr Justice Phillips ruled that the Barlow Clowes contract with
investors did not permit the alternative investment strategy adopted by Mr
Clowes. This did not necessarily mean, however, that the defendants' conduct
had been dishonest or criminal. That was for the jury to decide, he said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8 Photograph Christopher Newman arriving in court yesterday
before being acquitted in the Barlow Clowes trial (Omitted).
</PAGE>
