<PROFILE>_AN-CBKBQAEGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920211
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / The Barlow Clowes Trial: A baptism by fire for the novice
investment investigators - Richard Waters on whether regulators can stop
such crimes in the future
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JEREMY ORME, a towering accountant with a cadaverous pallor, is in the
front line of the UK's fight against investment fraud. A seasoned
investigator with the penetrating eye and clipped delivery of his calling,
he is moved to biblical references.
'Wickedness is like the green bay tree in the bible,' he says. 'Cut it down
and it will grow up again.'
Mr Orme is head of enforcement at the Securities and Investments Board, the
main investment watchdog. For him and the team of investigators he heads,
wickedness is tangible - the fraud and theft which deprives investors in
some cases of their life savings. None of them is prepared to say that
another Barlow Clowes will not happen.
'The moment we think we have done enough, we can be sure we will not have
done,' says Mr Orme. Mr Jim Gaskin, head of enforcement for Fimbra, the
regulatory body for independent financial advisers, agrees. 'If I said it
couldn't happen again, it would be a hostage to fortune, and of course it
would then happen tomorrow,' he says.
Yet both argue that the UK's system of investment regulation is far better
than it was. Closing Barlow Clowes was, in fact, one of the first successes
of the regime introduced under the 1986 Financial Services Act (FSA). After
years of dilatory action by the Department of Trade and Industry, SIB moved
to close Barlow Clowes in 1988 just days after it took on its full powers
under the act.
Before the act, investment regulation was administered by the DTI under the
Prevention of Fraud (Investments) Act. After it, a raft of new regulatory
bodies, led by SIB, was set up, each with its own team of investigators. The
teams are patched together with accountants, lawyers and assorted
experienced investigators from outside the investment world.
The Department of Trade and Industry no longer directly regulates the
investment industry. However, it too is taking its responsibilities under
the Companies Acts far more seriously after the bad publicity generated by
Barlow Clowes and other cases of the mid 1980s. Its investigations division
now employs 195, marking a 'significant increase in the past two years'.
Mr Gaskin at Fimbra points to some of the lessons that have been learnt in
the short time the act has been in force. Inspection visits on investment
firms are now targeted at those considered to carry the highest risk of
fraud: those with a single controlling director, for instance, or those
audited by a single accountant rather than a partnership. External signs,
such as the late filing of accounts or even the changing of an accounting
date, are monitored as signs of possible problems.
'They are much more focused visits now,' he says. 'There's a much better
assessment of where the risks are.'
Yet at least four weak links remain in the regulatory system. Each makes it
easier for investment frauds to be perpetrated, or delays the time it takes
for frauds to come to light.
The first is the role played by auditors in the regulatory system. Along
with an investment company's own board of directors, they are central to the
prevention of fraud. According to Mr Orme: 'It would be a grotesque waste of
national resource to think that corporate governance and auditing can count
for nothing, and that the specialist regulator has to start again.'
Faced with public concern that it was not doing more to fight fraud, the
auditing profession spent years arguing that the public misunderstood the
role of auditors before accepting that their role needed to be expanded. 'It
was very regrettable that the accountancy profession has taken so long,'
says Mr Orme, himself a former senior partner of Robson Rhodes, the
accountancy firm. He said he was disappointed that it had not been quicker
in its response to public concern. Mr Bill Morrison, chairman of the
Auditing Practices Board, accepted that accountants may have been slow to
act before, but said substantial changes were being proposed to meet public
concerns. 'The question now is whether we are being too ambitious in what we
are trying to achieve,' he said.
The second weak link is the unwillingness of professionals in the City to
'blow the whistle' when they suspect fraud. 'There needs to be a general
awakening about whistle-blowing,' says Mr Orme. Investment failures are
invariably followed by comments from City professionals that they suspected
something all along, he says. In spite of constant pleas from the regulators
and the Serious Fraud Office for greater help, the general attitude in the
City seems not to have changed.
The third weak link has been the people on whom the job of supervising the
investment world has fallen, though substantial headway has been made in
raising the quality of investigators in recent years. Low salaries are one
explanation; lack of experience another.
At the outset of the FSA regime, says Mr Gaskin, 'there were lots of people
around with auditing experience, but auditors are not responsible for
detecting fraud. We are - and we're getting better at it'.
The fourth problem has been the sheer number of investigatory bodies in the
City, each with overlapping interests. The political in-fighting and
jealousies this has created have at times spilled over into bad feeling
between regulators, though none has been bad-mannered enough to express it
publicly. Co-ordination between the regulators has improved as they have
learned to live with each other: but as the collapse of Bank of Credit and
Commerce International proved, 'colleges' of regulators all sharing
responsibility for a financial firm can fail dismally.
Ms Marjorie Mowlem, Labour's voice on City affairs, said that a Labour
government would 'streamline the regulatory system to prevent financial
advisers choosing the weak link in the web of regulatory institutions'.
The best defence probably rests with investors. Mr Gaskin says it is 'the
old, old story: if it looks too good to be true, it probably is.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
