<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / Government releases a salary surge: Recommendations of the
public-sector pay review bodies - Pressures building up over wages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOME TIME this year average gross weekly earnings in the public sector - now
Pounds 283 - are expected to overtake those in the private sector (Pounds
285). This will happen in one of the periodic surges in public-sector pay.
Yesterday's decision by the government to grant the pay-review body
recommendations in full, no doubt mindful of the imminence of polling day,
will not act as a brake on that surge.
The recommended increases, effective from April 1 - for the armed forces,
nurses, doctors, professions allied to medicine and teachers - average
nearly 6.5 per cent, with the teachers on 7.5 per cent pushing up that
average. The four pay-review bodies cover about 1.5m workers or 30 per cent
of public-sector employees.
Nearly half the public sector's 5m workers are covered by review bodies or
special comparability deals, which look at average earnings over the
preceding 12 months and thus tend to boost public-sector pay when inflation
is falling fast, as it has been recently.
The result, according to Mr Chris Trinder of the Public Finance Foundation,
the research arm of the Chartered Institute of Public Finance and
Accountancy, is that the rise in public-sector pay was 2 1/2 percentage
points above private-sector pay increases in 1991-92 and will be at least
one percentage point above the private sector and three percentage points
above inflation this year. Mr Trinder believes that the relatively generous
awards of the pay-review bodies are helping to create a 'two-tier' public
sector with a growing gap between the privileged pay-review groups and
others, such as local-government workers, who still bargain in the normal
way.
However, this year's pay-review settlement may help to pull up other
public-sector workers to increases of at least 5 per cent. The
non-industrial civil servants still have a private-sector comparability
system, which will probably give them about 5.5 per cent.
As manufacturing industry tries to hold down pay in order to stay
competitive within the European exchange rate mechanism, there are other
pressures that are likely to keep public-sector pay high over the next
couple of years
The pay-review bodies will not start pushing on performance-related pay for
doctors, nurses and teachers until next year. But the various attempts to
introduce more flexibility into public-sector pay will, in the medium-term,
increase earnings and not reduce them.
The Top Salaries Review Body recommendations, postponed until after the
election, are almost certain to propose enormous catch-up rises for top
civil servants, judges and generals which will seep down to lower levels.
Large private-sector employers, which are now agreeing rises of less than 5
per cent, will not thank the government for yesterday's decisions.
</TEXT>
