<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / Lloyd's Names close to clear victory on Outhwaite
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A GROUP of Lloyd's Names are close to winning a clear victory in the
out-of-court settlement being negotiated in the Outhwaite case.
Details of the settlement between 987 Names, who were members of Outhwaite
syndicate 317/661 in 1982, and 81 Lloyd's agents, including RHM Outhwaite
Underwriting, will be announced this morning.
The Names - the individuals whose capital supports underwriting at the
insurance market - are expected to win more than Pounds 100m from the
settlement which will be financed by errors and omissions insurers, who
cover agents against legal awards for negligence.
Errors and omissions policies, which are underwritten by Lloyd's syndicates,
also usually cover legal costs.
Syndicate 317/661's losses in the 1982 underwriting year amounted to more
than Pounds 200m and are expected to carry on rising.
Reports that a final settlement had been reached on Sunday night were
dismissed as 'premature' by sources close to the Names, who said
negotiations continued yesterday. Only those Names backing the legal action
will benefit, which will exclude the rest of the 1,614 Names on the
syndicate.
High Court hearings in the action, which began in October, have heard how Mr
Richard Outhwaite, the underwriter of syndicate 317/661, underwrote 32
loss-making reinsurance contracts, assuming the US liability exposures of
other insurers. When claims from awards to asbestosis victims mounted in the
mid-1980s, the syndicates produced disastrous results for Names.
Discussions about a possible out-of-court settlement are understood to have
begun about two weeks ago after an expert witness, Mr Richard Hazell,
finished giving his evidence on behalf of Mr Outhwaite. Mr Justice Saville
adjourned the hearings for a week on Monday last week.
Mr David Coleridge, the chairman of Lloyd's, is said to have been involved
in the initial talks between the 1982 Outhwaite Names Association and the
agents' errors and omissions insurers.
A settlement in the case is likely to encourage other Names also involved in
legal action against their agents. Four legal cases - involving Names on
syndicates managed by Pulbrook, Poland and Oakeley Vaughan - are
outstanding.
A High Court judge yesterday issued disqualification orders against two
former Lloyd's underwriters. Mr Peter Cameron-Webb and Mr Peter Dixon,
formerly of the PCW Agencies, were disqualified from being involved in the
management of companies for 10 years.
The two were accused of 'dishonest and cynical plunder' in a DTI report
published 18 months ago.
</TEXT>
