<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / Warning on performance rises: Recommendations of the
public-sector pay review bodies - Doctors and dentists
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE review body for doctors and dentists warned about the difficulties of
introducing performance-related pay as it recommended rises of 5.5 per cent
for all of the group covered except general dental practitioners (GDPs) who
were awarded 8.5 per cent.
It said it was concerned about government plans to constrain money available
for performance-related pay after health-service officials said they would
not be looking to 'fund pay flexibility' from outside recommended general
increases
The review body said the incentive impact of performance-pay schemes would
be weakened if they were seen as being automatically set against future pay
rises.
Its recommendations will mean a 6 per cent rise in the pay bill for 106,000
doctors and dentists at a cost of Pounds 314m.
In recommending an increase of 8.5 per cent for GDPs, the review body said
it took into account the business difficulties experienced by practices and
the evidence of an increased workload under a new contract.
It also noted the trend in the values of pensions and fringe packages which
showed GDPs at a particular disadvantage to comparable professions outside
the health service.
In spite of the review body's recommendations the British Medical
Association said that doctors would see average earnings rise by only 3 per
cent because of a clawback of money paid this year which resulted from
targets being exceeded. It is understood that some dentists will suffer a
similar effect.
The review body's recommendations would take the average net remuneration of
a general medical practitioner to Pounds 40,010 from April 1 and that of
general dental practitioners to Pounds 35,815.
Review Body on Doctors' and Dentists Remuneration, HMSO. Pounds 7.70.
</TEXT>
