<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / Inflation-beating increase contrasts with redundancies:
Recommendations of the public-sector pay review bodies - Armed Services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE AVERAGE 6 per cent pay award recommended for the armed forces
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
297,000-strong but declining - was at the upper end of expectations after a
relatively generous increase last year.
It comes as Army personnel await the first wave of redundancies under the
government's planned cuts in service strength.
'We were not anticipating anything extraordinary,' an Army officer commented
yesterday.
The review body, chaired by Sir Peter Cazalet, recommended a general
increase of 5.9 per cent, with some categories of warrant officer receiving
a higher 7.9 per cent to bring them more into line with comparable civilian
jobs.
Under the increases the pay of a Royal Navy lieutenant with six years in the
rank will rise from Pounds 23,007 to Pounds 24,302. A Lieutenant Colonel or
Wing Commander will receive Pounds 36,964, up from Pounds 35,001.
The pay levels include the so-called X factor, designed to reflect the
special hardships of service life. This now stands at 11.5 per cent of the
basic pay, after being increased last year.
Pay scales for officers promoted from the ranks are being uprated.
Increments for long-serving non-commissioned officers are also to be
increased, but the review body questioned the effectiveness of the current
system.
The recommendations are expected to add Pounds 291.9m to the armed forces'
salary bill including the cost of reserves. But higher charges for food and
accommodation will recover about Pounds 17.7m of the extra cost.
The estimated 5.9 per cent increase in the pay bill for regular forces
compares with 12.2 per cent last year when the armed services was the only
public-sector group to have the rise paid in full rather than by stages.
That increase came in the middle of the Gulf war.
In its recommendations, the review body said it had to take account of 'much
uncertainty about future roles and jobs' following the announcement last
summer of plans to reduce numbers of regular personnel by 62,000. The
remuneration package played 'no small part' in servicemen's motivation, it
said.
A first batch of redundancies, mostly voluntary, is due to be announced
later this month involving about 850 army officers and 2,500 soldiers.
Review Body on Armed Forces' Pay, HMSO, Pounds 6.25.
