<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / Pay rises above inflation for 1.5m public employees: Review
body average of 6.5% accepted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, PETER NORMAN and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT decided yesterday to grant pay increases to 1.5m public
employees at well above the rate of inflation.
This means that pay rises in the public sector are running between 34 and
107 per cent higher than the latest average of increases in manufacturing
industry.
The government accepted in full review-body recommend-ations for raising the
pay of the armed forces, nurses, doctors, professions allied to medicine and
teachers by between 5.5 per cent and 8.5 per cent.
The increases will average nearly 6.5 per cent, and take effect from April
1, ahead of the widely expected general election date of April 9.
At the same time, the Confederation of British Industry reported that pay
settlements in manufacturing industry fell to their lowest level since it
began collecting such data in 1980.
Latest figures from the CBI pay data bank showed that settlements in
manufacturing averaged only 4.1 per cent in the final quarter of last year,
down on the 5.1 per cent recorded in last year's third quarter and under
half the 9 per cent average rises recorded in the final quarter of 1990.
Yesterday's rises cover around 30 per cent of public sector employees and
are the first to be awarded in full since 1989. They will cost the taxpayer
about Pounds 1.84bn and are expected in the course of the year to lift the
average weekly pay packet of public sector employees above that of private
sector employees.
The government's decision to award pay rises at well above the present 4.5
per cent rate of inflation drew strong criticism from some opposition
politicians. It was denounced as a 'cynical volte-face' by Mr Alex Carlile,
the Liberal Democrat party's economics spokesman, while Mr Jack Straw,
Labour's education spokesman, pointed out that the last time teachers
received a significant real pay increase 'was just before the 1987
election'.
The government responded by saying these were the lowest awards for many
years and covered groups which had not done well in the past. There was no
significant move in the direction of performance related pay for any of the
groups. But performance pay, favoured by the government, will be a feature
of next year's awards.
Among the various professions, general dental practitioners emerged with the
highest pay increases: they received 8.5 per cent to reflect recruitment
difficulties in the profession and an increased workload.
But with a 7.5 per cent across-the-board increase in all scales from April,
420,000 teachers in England and Wales did better than any other public
sector group in the pay review awards. Their increase is on top of the 9.5
per cent awarded to teachers last year.
The total value of the teachers' award is 7.8 per cent, taking the average
classroom teacher's salary - including allowances - to Pounds 18,200. Mr
Kenneth Clarke, education secretary, said the award was 'greater than the
government had contemplated'. He defend-ed the decision to give teachers
review-body status as 'an essential step in restoring the status of the
teaching profession'.
The armed forces will receive an average increase of 6 per cent; doctors 5.5
per cent while nurses will get rises of between 5.6 per cent and 6 per cent
based on grading. The spread for the professions allied to medicine is 6.2
per cent to 6.5 per cent.
The Top Salaries Review Body was not included in the announcement. The
government agreed to the request from the review body to delay its report
until mid-year, so it would not be affected by electoral considerations. It
is expected to recommend large catch-up rises for top civil servants, judges
and generals.
