<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / Clowes awaits sentence for theft and fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, NEIL BUCKLEY and RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Peter Clowes, the man behind the most spectacular UK investment scandal
of the 1980s, was yesterday found guilty on 18 counts of theft and fraud, 3
1/2 years after the Pounds 150m collapse of his investment company, Barlow
Clowes.
He was led from court in handcuffs and detained at Brixton prison overnight,
before being sentenced this morning at the Old Bailey.
A business associate of Mr Clowes, Mr Peter Naylor, was found guilty on one
count of theft, but cleared of other theft and conspiracy to defraud
charges.
Two other associates - Mr Guy Cramer and Mr Christopher Newman - were both
acquitted of all charges against them in a day of mixed success for the
Serious Fraud Office, which brought the prosecution.
More than Pounds 113m had been 'milked' from the funds of mainly elderly
clients, who had been led to believe they were investing in secure
gilt-edged stock, the jury was told during the seven month trial.
Much of the money was spent by Mr Clowes on buying up other companies and a
luxurious lifestyle which included the purchase of a yacht, an executive jet
and a French chateau. The collapse of Barlow Clowes has cost the British
taxpayer Pounds 150m, paid out in compensation by the government after an
unprecedented campaign by investors.
In an interview ahead of the verdicts, Mr Clowes insisted that he had acted
within the investment guidelines of his company. Speaking at the end of last
week, he reserved his harshest criticism for Spicer &amp; Oppenheim, the Barlow
Clowes auditor which has since merged with Touche Ross.
He said the auditors must have known what Barlow Clowes was doing with
investors' money, and have sanctioned it. If the auditors thought the
company only invested in gilts (UK government bonds) they should have
questioned the lack of gilt certificates in the company, he said. 'Did they
just think Pounds 100m was sitting in a bank?'
Mr Clowes sat stony-faced as the verdicts were returned, but his wife Pamela
shook her head in disbelief and his daughter ran from the courtroom in
tears.
Much of the evidence heard over 108 days was highly complex and related to
the details of the money laundering operations set up by Mr Clowes. Thanking
the jury, Mr Justice Phillips said: 'Until recent times, no one could have
imagined that our legal system could place such a burden on anyone's time.'
At a press conference after the verdicts were delivered, Mr Cramer
criticised the prosecution brought against him by the SFO. He said no
evidence had been produced to show that he knew of any fraud within Barlow
Clowes and he had been tried on a 'guilt by association' basis.
Outside the court, Mr Newman said he was 'delighted that the ordeal of the
last three years is now over'.
Landmark case of old-fashioned theft Page 8
</TEXT>
