<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / International Company News: Northern Telecom and Motorola
form venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOTOROLA of the US and Northern Telecom of Canada yesterday unveiled plans
to pool more than Dollars 200m of assets and form a joint venture to market
cellular telephone network systems in North and South America.
The venture - between the leading US electronics and semiconductor
manufacturer and the Canadian-based telecoms group - is aimed at stepping up
competition against American Telephone &amp; Telegraph (AT&amp;T) and Ericsson of
Sweden, the leaders in the cellular switching sector.
The new company, to be called Motorola-Nortel Communications, is expected to
have 1992 sales of more than Dollars 500m, according to Mr William Spencer,
a Motorola vice president who will become chief executive of the new 50-50
venture.
Mr Spencer said the venture would sell, service and support cellular
infrastructure systems in all areas of North, central and South America,
including the Caribbean region.
The venture is to be based in Chicago and will consist of between Dollars
200m and Dollars 300m of assets that are being pooled. Some 600 Motorola and
300 Northern Telecom employees will be transferred to the venture.
The North American cellular telephone network sector is estimated to have
annual sales of around Dollars 1.4bn, with a compound growth rate of around
40 per cent a year.
</TEXT>
