<DOCNO>FT921-9692</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CBKBQABKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920211
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the third of its 'Fin de Siecle' conversations, Without Walls asks
whether the cold war has given way to a new conflict between east and west
in which Japan will move to the top of the heap and use the USA as its bread
basket and Europe as its boutique. Some people, such as William Rees-Mogg,
have moved beyond that scenario to worry about the one after, when the
economic capital of the world will be not Tokyo but 'Hong Kong or some other
Chinese city' (9.00 C4). ITV's documentary series Murder Squad (9.00) is
concerned with an explosion at a hairdresser in London's New Cross. That is
followed by the first episode in a new batch of That's Love (9.30) a rather
superior comedy starring Jimmy Mulville and Diana Hardcastle as a middle
class couple dealing with the vicissitudes of marriage in the 90s. Today
Tony Slattery appears for the first time, playing a marriage guidance
counsellor. Viewpoint 92 tells the story of journalist Geoffrey Lean who
went into hospital for a minor operation last year and woke three weeks
later paralysed and unable to speak. He says 'I believe that if my case had
been decided on a cost-benefit basis I wouldn't be here to tell the tale'
(10.40 ITV).
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
