FT  11 FEB 92 / Potterton Myson to close boiler factory
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POTTERTON Myson, part of Blue Circle Industries, yesterday announced the
closure of its domestic boiler factory at Birtley, Co Durham, with the loss
of 302 jobs.
The company, which hopes to redeploy about 10 per cent of the Birtley
workforce, said output would be transferred to the factory's sister plants
at Padiham, Lancashire, and Warwick.
Acquisition of Myson Group in late 1989 had given Potterton Myson more
manufacturing capacity than was needed to meet expected demand. That was the
main reason for the Birtley closure, the company said.
Mr Peter Taylor, director and general manager at Birtley, said: 'If it
didn't happen now I fear we would die by starvation.' He added that the
plant was essentially an assembly operation lacking core technology, whereas
Warwick and Padiham manufactured the heat exchangers used in the company's
gas central-heating boilers. 'Today if you want to invest you have to invest
in your core technology,' he added.
Mr Taylor declined to disclose how much the recession's impact on
housebuilding had hit demand for Birtley's boilers. But he said it had
depressed the market considerably.
The AEU engineering workers' union, which represents most of the workforce,
said it was monitoring the situation.
'The employees have been devastated by the news and are in a state of
bewilderment,' said Mr Davey Hall, Tyne district secretary.
</TEXT>
