<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / Unit trust body backs down on retail regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UNIT Trust Association has reversed its position on retail regulation in
a revised paper submitted to the Securities and Investments Board. The move
is a result of pressure from its life assurance company members.
Five of the trade association's largest life assurance members resigned
after it submitted a paper to SIB which criticised life assurance sales
practices in unusually harsh terms. The five members contribute 10 per cent
of the associations's revenues.
In its most significant reversal, the new paper from the association no
longer offers unequivocal support for the SIB proposal on 'depolarisation',
which would have allowed unit trusts to be sold through more outlets than
are presently available for life assurance products. Instead, the paper now
simply says that while some members support the concept, others are opposed
to it.
Sales of all products are currently polarised - that is, they must be sold
either through tied or direct agents selling the products of a single
company, or through independent financial advisers selling the products of
many suppliers. The association had argued that as charges relating to the
sales of unit trusts are easily visible to prospective buyers, unlike those
of life products, the consumer protection afforded by polarisation was
unnecessary.
The paper also climbed down on SIB proposals to require tougher disclosure
rules in the sale of life products. The life assurance industry has been
fighting many of these proposals, arguing that to give too much information
to consumers would confuse many of them.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-9712</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CBKBQAA0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920211
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / Recommendations of the Public-Sector Pay Review Bodies:
Award 'greater than contemplated' - Teachers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SUBSTANTIAL pay rise for teachers has been on the cards since Mr John
Major appointed an independent review body to assess their pay shortly after
becoming prime minister. It was a calculated attempt to raise teachers'
morale - and with it the Tories' flagging support in the public sector.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, education secretary, admitted yesterday that the 7.5 per
cent award to the 420,000 teachers in England and Wales was 'greater than
the government had contemplated'. But ministers had pledged to honour the
review body's findings in full, and with the rise due to take effect on
April 1 - a week before the most likely election date - staggering its
implementation was not an option.
The rise takes the low on the teachers' scale from Pounds 10,404 to Pounds
11,184, and the top point from Pounds 17,523 to Pounds 18,837 plus
allowances. A good honours graduate will start on at least Pounds 12,300 -
Pounds 14,200 in inner London. The top of the head-teachers' scale - for
heads of large secondary schools - rises from Pounds 46,680 to Pounds
50,181.
Primary teachers do best in the settlement. An additional 26,000 incentive
allowances - more than one extra per school - will be available from
September, worth between Pounds 1,296 and Pounds 4,000 each. By then, more
than half of all teachers will be receiving an allowance.
Incentive allowances are to be payable not only for special responsibility
but for 'excellent classroom performance'. That apart, the review body,
chaired by Sir Graham Day, chairman of British Aerospace, has refused to
rush the creation of a full-blown performance-pay regime for teachers.
However, with one in three teachers leaving the profession in their first
five years, the review body said it was 'concerned to avert complacency on
teacher quality', and it intends to work up a performance-pay scheme for
introduction in 1993-94.
The settlement will add 7.8 per cent to the teachers' pay bill, which local
authorities will have to meet. The government announced yesterday that it
would provide local government with an extra Pounds 60m to bridge the gap
between the pay settlement and the government's 7.2 per cent allowance for
extra education spending in the 1992-93 rate-support grant settlement.
However, local authority leaders claimed that the 7.2 per cent allowed only
for only 3.7 per cent of extra spending, once last year's pay award and
demographic trends are accounted for. Most authorities - which have to set
budgets before the end of this month. - have allowed only between 5 and 6
per cent in their provisional spending plans.
Some county councils will make up the shortfall from reserves. But with
average county council reserves projected at only 3.3 per cent of budgeted
spending for the next financial year, many will be forced to seek savings
elsewhere.
The Labour-controlled Association of Metropolitan Authorities claimed
yesterday that the 'funding gap' amounted to Pounds 300m, and predicted cuts
in teacher numbers and school budgets.
Even with the pay rise, the review body concluded that 'teacher shortages
are more likely than surpluses' in the next few years, and that high wastage
rates were likely to result in 'serious teacher shortages in some areas.'
School Teachers' Review Body, HMSO. Pounds 8.20.
</TEXT>
