<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / Treasury admission on housing downturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Treasury has admitted that its forecasting techniques have failed to
take into account the effect of the depression in the housing market on the
the recession, Peter Marsh writes.
The admission has taken the form of a series of changes to the mathematical
equations in the Treasury's computer model of how the economy functions. The
model acts as a base for the department's economic forecasts.
Mr Brian Pearce, chief economist at the Ernst &amp; Young Item Club, a
forecasting group, said the new equations could indicate that the Treasury
was considering changes to fiscal policy in the Budget. One possibility
could be to raise the Pounds 30,000 ceiling on mortgage relief.
The Treasury said the changes were technical and 'not significant'.
</TEXT>
