<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / BBC makes offer on copyright fees ahead of tribunal ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BBC has made publishers a new offer on copyright payments several weeks
before the Copyright Tribunal is due to rule on the issue.
The move by BBC Enterprises came last month following the tribunal hearing
which opened on November 12 and ended on December 20. A decision is not
expected before the end of this month.
Copyright fees became controversial last year after deregulation of the
television listings market. The government decided to end what Mr Douglas
Hurd, then home secretary, called the 'dotty duopoly' of Radio Times and TV
Times. All programme listings had henceforth to be provided to publishers in
return for a copyright fee.
The Newspaper Publishers' Association, which represents national newspapers;
the Newspaper Society, representing regional newspapers; Time Out, the
London listings magazine; Hello, the national magazine; and the Surrey
Advertiser group, representing the interests of weekly newspapers,
complained to the tribunal that the fees were too high.
Mr Tony Elliott, publisher of Time Out, and a long-time opponent of the
listings duopoly said yesterday he was 'amazed' that BBC Enterprises,
publisher of Radio Times, should have offered a deal before the tribunal
decision was known.
Mr Elliott said he believed the 'without-prejudice' offer went first to the
Newspaper Society and was later sent to the other parties.
The offer is believed to involved considerable reductions in the present
rate card.
Mr John Mellon, chairman of IPC Magazines, publisher of TV Times and What's
on TV, yesterday also expressed surprise that the BBC should have made an
offer when it did.
IPC, which owns copyright in ITV programmes until the end of this year, said
that it will await the tribunal's verdict and does not intend to make any
offers to publishers.
It is believed that Newspaper Society lawyers have been in contact with BBC
lawyers since the without prejudice offer was received but it is not clear
if there is any chance of an agreement.
The BBC action is being interpreted by publishing groups as a sign that the
corporation may be taking a pessimistic view of the outcome of the Copyright
Tribunal hearings.
</TEXT>
